1
00:03:14,100 --> 00:03:16,850
<i>By the end of the World War
Tomainia weakened.</i>

2
00:03:17,140 --> 00:03:20,850
<i>Revolution had broken out,
her diplomats sued for peace</i>

3
00:03:21,070 --> 00:03:23,060
<i>while Tomainia's army fought on,</i>

4
00:03:23,360 --> 00:03:27,660
<i>confident its war machine
would smash the enemy's lines.</i>

5
00:03:28,120 --> 00:03:30,610
<i>Big Bertha, able to fire 100 miles,</i>

6
00:03:30,920 --> 00:03:33,130
<i>was to make its appearance
on the Western Front,</i>

7
00:03:33,420 --> 00:03:35,960
<i>and strike terror into the enemy.</i>

8
00:03:36,260 --> 00:03:40,640
<i>75 miles away was her target:
the cathedral of Notre-Dame.</i>

9
00:03:43,520 --> 00:03:46,530
Range: 95,452.

10
00:03:49,320 --> 00:03:50,740
Stand clear!

11
00:03:50,990 --> 00:03:51,820
Fire!

12
00:04:09,940 --> 00:04:11,410
Stand by your trigger!

13
00:04:12,700 --> 00:04:15,990
Range correction: 95,455.

14
00:04:19,800 --> 00:04:20,790
Breach secured.

15
00:04:21,220 --> 00:04:22,250
Stand clear.

16
00:04:22,470 --> 00:04:24,340
Ready... Fire!

17
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:42,570
Defective shell. We'll examine it.

18
00:04:52,940 --> 00:04:54,100
Check the fuse.

19
00:04:54,400 --> 00:04:55,600
Yes, the fuse.

20
00:05:30,920 --> 00:05:32,670
Look out! Run!

21
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:48,950
What's that?

22
00:05:49,160 --> 00:05:50,870
- Air raid.
- After Big Bertha.

23
00:05:51,170 --> 00:05:52,630
The anti-aircraft gun!

24
00:05:52,920 --> 00:05:54,170
To the gun!

25
00:06:20,600 --> 00:06:21,880
Have you gone crazy?

26
00:06:22,890 --> 00:06:24,090
Come down!

27
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:39,000
What do you think you're doing?
Have you gone crazy?

28
00:06:39,290 --> 00:06:43,050
Sir, the enemy have broken through.
Every man to the front.

29
00:06:43,340 --> 00:06:46,050
Muster the gun crew!

30
00:06:48,690 --> 00:06:51,520
Get your hand grenades, soldiers.

31
00:06:52,280 --> 00:06:55,650
Where's your hand grenade?

32
00:06:56,490 --> 00:06:58,150
Give him one.

33
00:07:03,250 --> 00:07:05,660
Keep moving. Come along, hurry up!

34
00:07:07,390 --> 00:07:09,350
Pardon me, but to work this...

35
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:12,010
Pull the pin,
count to ten and throw it!

36
00:07:24,790 --> 00:07:25,990
Let them have it!

37
00:07:47,210 --> 00:07:48,830
This is no time to scratch.

38
00:07:53,470 --> 00:07:54,930
Pull yourself together.

39
00:07:55,970 --> 00:07:57,010
Take this.

40
00:07:58,520 --> 00:07:59,680
Forward!

41
00:08:01,020 --> 00:08:01,810
Fall in!

42
00:08:03,400 --> 00:08:05,200
Hey you, come on!

43
00:08:10,500 --> 00:08:12,080
Order arms!

44
00:08:14,720 --> 00:08:16,170
Prepare to attack.

45
00:08:16,470 --> 00:08:17,800
Forward!

46
00:08:59,420 --> 00:09:00,500
There you are.

47
00:09:12,190 --> 00:09:14,860
The enemy!
Come on, let's get him!

48
00:09:23,090 --> 00:09:24,370
May I come in, sir?

49
00:09:24,590 --> 00:09:26,470
- Who is it?
- Friend.

50
00:09:31,270 --> 00:09:33,510
- What division?
- 21st artillery, sir.

51
00:09:33,820 --> 00:09:36,730
Take this and keep firing.
I'll be back.

52
00:09:56,150 --> 00:09:57,640
Comrade! Help!

53
00:10:03,700 --> 00:10:04,610
What is it?

54
00:10:04,620 --> 00:10:07,740
I'm exhausted.
Quick, help me to my plane.

55
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:14,500
Thank you. I'll see you get
the Tomainian Cross for this.

56
00:10:14,850 --> 00:10:17,640
Only too willing to oblige, sir.

57
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:28,740
You saved my life. Thank you.

58
00:10:29,040 --> 00:10:30,240
I'll strap you in.

59
00:10:30,540 --> 00:10:33,790
I can't make it alone.
You'll have to stay with me.

60
00:10:34,880 --> 00:10:36,000
Can you fly?

61
00:10:36,300 --> 00:10:37,550
I can try.

62
00:10:39,140 --> 00:10:42,260
Lift my hand to the stick.
I haven't the strength.

63
00:10:43,480 --> 00:10:44,860
Take charge of that gun!

64
00:10:46,400 --> 00:10:49,410
The enemy!
Quick, lift my hand to the throttle.

65
00:10:51,620 --> 00:10:52,900
We'll fool 'em!

66
00:11:14,450 --> 00:11:16,080
Hold on to these dispatches.

67
00:11:16,500 --> 00:11:18,620
If we get them
to General Schmelloffel,

68
00:11:18,840 --> 00:11:20,420
Tomainia may yet win.

69
00:11:22,590 --> 00:11:23,790
I'm going to faint.

70
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:25,290
Don't say that.

71
00:11:26,470 --> 00:11:27,590
Sorry.

72
00:11:35,910 --> 00:11:36,900
Where am I?

73
00:11:37,200 --> 00:11:38,480
Don't you know me?

74
00:11:41,380 --> 00:11:43,250
Yes, I feel better now.

75
00:11:43,710 --> 00:11:45,590
The blood's returning to my head.

76
00:11:45,800 --> 00:11:47,130
What's below?

77
00:11:47,640 --> 00:11:48,840
The sun?

78
00:11:49,770 --> 00:11:51,050
Shining upwards.

79
00:11:51,350 --> 00:11:53,350
Strange. How's the gas?

80
00:11:53,610 --> 00:11:55,020
Kept me awake all night.

81
00:11:55,230 --> 00:11:57,310
No, the gasoline in the tank!

82
00:11:58,450 --> 00:11:59,230
Almost empty.

83
00:11:59,530 --> 00:12:02,320
We must be nearly there.
What time is it?

84
00:12:04,120 --> 00:12:07,160
Approximately one minute to twelve.

85
00:12:12,470 --> 00:12:13,640
Strange.

86
00:12:20,450 --> 00:12:23,070
We seem to be defying
the laws of gravity.

87
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:31,080
Water. Quick, I'm going to faint.

88
00:12:31,420 --> 00:12:32,460
Wait a while.

89
00:12:33,550 --> 00:12:38,050
We'll get into trouble
if you faint any more.

90
00:12:38,390 --> 00:12:39,560
Just hold it.

91
00:12:40,900 --> 00:12:42,390
I think I... Now...

92
00:12:50,250 --> 00:12:51,490
Take it!

93
00:12:52,710 --> 00:12:53,990
Something's wrong.

94
00:12:55,050 --> 00:12:56,590
I can't reach it.

95
00:12:59,970 --> 00:13:01,060
It's all gone.

96
00:13:02,020 --> 00:13:03,050
What's the matter?

97
00:13:03,310 --> 00:13:04,310
Belt too tight.

98
00:13:04,610 --> 00:13:05,350
Loosen it.

99
00:13:05,650 --> 00:13:06,570
I'm trying to!

100
00:13:09,330 --> 00:13:10,400
We're upside down.

101
00:13:10,700 --> 00:13:11,610
I know it!

102
00:13:11,700 --> 00:13:12,490
The stick!

103
00:13:12,790 --> 00:13:13,820
Impossible.

104
00:13:14,670 --> 00:13:17,240
There it goes. We're out of gas.

105
00:13:17,760 --> 00:13:21,380
Well, I suppose this is the end.
Cigarette?

106
00:13:21,680 --> 00:13:22,680
Not now!

107
00:13:22,930 --> 00:13:24,430
I shan't need this any more.

108
00:13:25,020 --> 00:13:26,350
What month is it?

109
00:13:26,560 --> 00:13:30,070
April. Spring in Tomainia.

110
00:13:30,280 --> 00:13:31,740
Hilda will be in the garden,

111
00:13:31,950 --> 00:13:33,330
tending the daffodils.

112
00:13:33,990 --> 00:13:36,120
How she loves daffodils!

113
00:13:36,790 --> 00:13:39,550
She'd never cut them
for fear of hurting them.

114
00:13:39,960 --> 00:13:43,000
It was like taking a life
to cut a daffodil.

115
00:13:43,930 --> 00:13:46,050
Sweet, gentle Hilda.

116
00:13:52,110 --> 00:13:53,740
A beautiful soul.

117
00:13:54,240 --> 00:13:58,540
She loved animals,
and little children, too.

118
00:14:03,840 --> 00:14:05,750
We've landed! Dispatches!

119
00:14:06,590 --> 00:14:08,010
Comrade, where are you?

120
00:14:14,610 --> 00:14:17,280
The dispatches... Where are they?

121
00:14:20,620 --> 00:14:23,910
- Are you hurt?
- Take me to General Schmelloffel.

122
00:14:24,210 --> 00:14:26,920
If we don't deliver these,
we're defeated.

123
00:14:27,130 --> 00:14:28,460
- The war's over.
- What?

124
00:14:28,680 --> 00:14:29,710
We lost.

125
00:15:26,030 --> 00:15:28,520
<i>Hynkel takes power.
The Jewish soldier</i>

126
00:15:28,780 --> 00:15:33,450
<i>suffered a loss of memory
and remained in hospital for years,</i>

127
00:15:33,670 --> 00:15:36,340
<i>ignorant of the change in Tomainia.</i>

128
00:15:36,590 --> 00:15:39,050
<i>Hynkel ruled the nation
with an iron fist.</i>

129
00:15:39,260 --> 00:15:43,100
<i>Under the double-cross emblem
liberty was banished.</i>

130
00:15:43,390 --> 00:15:45,720
<i>Only the voice of Hynkel was heard.</i>

131
00:16:30,140 --> 00:16:31,310
<i>Adenoid Hynkel said,</i>

132
00:16:31,640 --> 00:16:34,430
<i>"Tomainia was down
but today has risen."</i>

133
00:16:54,600 --> 00:16:56,060
<i>"Democracy is fragrant."</i>

134
00:16:58,320 --> 00:16:59,940
<i>"Liberty is odious."</i>

135
00:17:02,780 --> 00:17:04,990
<i>"Freedom of speech
is objectionable."</i>

136
00:17:08,540 --> 00:17:10,670
<i>"Tomainia has the greatest army."</i>

137
00:17:12,680 --> 00:17:14,470
<i>"The greatest navy."</i>

138
00:17:18,940 --> 00:17:21,390
<i>"But to remain great
we must sacrifice."</i>

139
00:17:25,280 --> 00:17:26,910
<i>"We must tighten our belts."</i>

140
00:17:43,020 --> 00:17:46,280
<i>He now speaks to Field Marshal
Herring, Minister of War.</i>

141
00:17:56,670 --> 00:17:59,340
<i>Now Herr Garbitsch,
Minister of the Interior.</i>

142
00:18:09,820 --> 00:18:11,980
<i>He remembers his early struggles,</i>

143
00:18:12,240 --> 00:18:14,700
<i>shared by his two loyal comrades.</i>

144
00:19:50,170 --> 00:19:52,240
<i>A reference to the Jewish people.</i>

145
00:20:45,720 --> 00:20:48,560
<i>The Phooey remarks
that for the world</i>

146
00:20:48,850 --> 00:20:51,060
<i>he has peace in his heart.</i>

147
00:21:21,620 --> 00:21:23,780
<i>We now pause
for station identification.</i>

148
00:21:24,460 --> 00:21:27,210
<i>This is the Pari-Mutual network,
bringing you</i>

149
00:21:27,510 --> 00:21:30,430
<i>Hynkel's address to the children
of the double-cross.</i>

150
00:21:30,720 --> 00:21:31,720
<i>The interpreter</i>

151
00:21:31,930 --> 00:21:34,140
<i>is Hynkel's personal translator,</i>

152
00:21:34,440 --> 00:21:36,850
<i>reading from a prepared manuscript.</i>

153
00:21:37,190 --> 00:21:40,400
<i>Stand by for further commentary.
Go ahead, Tomainia.</i>

154
00:21:41,110 --> 00:21:43,520
<i>His Excellency
is about to descend the stairs.</i>

155
00:21:51,510 --> 00:21:54,430
Your Excellency, are you hurt?

156
00:22:26,190 --> 00:22:27,570
Ride in the other car.

157
00:22:36,840 --> 00:22:38,040
<i>His Excellency</i>

158
00:22:38,260 --> 00:22:41,710
<i>seems pleased as he is greeted
by Tomainian children.</i>

159
00:22:42,890 --> 00:22:45,270
<i>He pauses before a woman
with a child.</i>

160
00:22:48,490 --> 00:22:49,730
Camera!

161
00:22:50,570 --> 00:22:52,150
<i>Even the baby is thrilled</i>

162
00:22:52,370 --> 00:22:54,580
<i>and seems all smiles
at the attention.</i>

163
00:23:19,790 --> 00:23:21,950
<i>His Excellency leaves the scene</i>

164
00:23:22,210 --> 00:23:23,920
<i>and will return
along Hynkelstrasse,</i>

165
00:23:24,170 --> 00:23:27,210
<i>where he'll pass Tomainia's
modern masterpieces:</i>

166
00:23:27,560 --> 00:23:30,130
<i>the Venus of Today
and the Thinker of Tomorrow.</i>

167
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:40,530
- How was it?
- The speech?

168
00:23:41,370 --> 00:23:42,620
Very good.

169
00:23:42,960 --> 00:23:45,880
Your reference to the Jews
might have been more violent.

170
00:23:46,090 --> 00:23:47,040
What?

171
00:23:47,260 --> 00:23:48,750
To arouse the people's anger.

172
00:23:49,050 --> 00:23:53,000
Violence against the Jews might make
the people forget their stomach.

173
00:23:54,390 --> 00:23:57,850
You're right. Things have been quiet
in the ghetto lately.

174
00:24:22,320 --> 00:24:23,690
Good morning, Mr. Jaeckel.

175
00:24:24,360 --> 00:24:25,400
What's good about it?

176
00:24:25,830 --> 00:24:27,540
Conditions could be worse.

177
00:24:27,950 --> 00:24:30,990
If you think so,
you have a great imagination.

178
00:24:31,420 --> 00:24:33,290
You heard Hynkel's speech.

179
00:24:33,710 --> 00:24:36,630
I heard nothing.
I've got my own troubles.

180
00:24:37,140 --> 00:24:39,810
You're better off
than a lot of people.

181
00:24:40,140 --> 00:24:41,390
What about the barber?

182
00:24:42,020 --> 00:24:43,430
Still in hospital.

183
00:24:43,730 --> 00:24:46,020
He's been there since the war.

184
00:24:47,660 --> 00:24:49,820
Why not rent
his barbershop for him?

185
00:24:50,410 --> 00:24:54,740
He won't let me. Every few weeks
he writes to say he's coming back.

186
00:24:55,460 --> 00:24:57,870
A pity it should be idle
all these years.

187
00:24:58,470 --> 00:24:59,960
Why worry?

188
00:25:00,300 --> 00:25:03,090
The government
will soon take it from him.

189
00:25:03,390 --> 00:25:07,100
Perhaps you're right.
Not such a good morning after all.

190
00:25:07,730 --> 00:25:09,190
Now you said it.

191
00:25:10,700 --> 00:25:11,730
Hannah.

192
00:25:13,290 --> 00:25:17,040
On the mantelpiece is my tobacco
pouch. Will you get it?

193
00:25:19,670 --> 00:25:21,330
Everyone is full of troubles.

194
00:25:21,630 --> 00:25:25,300
Yeah, everyone.
Look at Hannah, poor girl.

195
00:25:25,600 --> 00:25:27,840
A hard worker, can't get a job.

196
00:25:28,140 --> 00:25:31,230
Father was killed in the war,
mother died last year.

197
00:25:31,740 --> 00:25:33,860
Can't earn enough to pay her rent.

198
00:25:34,160 --> 00:25:36,650
What can I do?
I can't throw her out.

199
00:25:45,760 --> 00:25:46,960
You need some more.

200
00:25:47,180 --> 00:25:50,130
- Where are you going?
- Mrs. Shoemaker's laundry.

201
00:25:50,390 --> 00:25:54,770
You'd better take the key.
Mrs. Jaeckel and I are going out.

202
00:25:55,110 --> 00:25:56,230
I'm locking up

203
00:25:56,490 --> 00:26:00,190
in case the storm troopers
start their monkey business again.

204
00:26:12,640 --> 00:26:17,470
<i>Aryan! We're Aryans!</i>

205
00:26:17,730 --> 00:26:20,900
<i>And we go marching by!</i>

206
00:26:21,950 --> 00:26:25,450
Look, fellows!
Tomatoes and potatoes.

207
00:26:28,040 --> 00:26:29,790
I'll take a box home.

208
00:26:33,760 --> 00:26:35,010
Hey, the lorry.

209
00:26:35,720 --> 00:26:37,630
Hold it there, will you?

210
00:26:40,070 --> 00:26:41,440
You have no right!

211
00:26:41,690 --> 00:26:43,900
Just charge it to my account!

212
00:26:47,620 --> 00:26:49,330
Nice ripe tomatoes.

213
00:26:49,540 --> 00:26:51,500
Why don't some of you
do something?

214
00:26:52,050 --> 00:26:53,620
If I were a man I'd show you.

215
00:26:54,420 --> 00:26:55,920
What would you do, pretty?

216
00:26:56,340 --> 00:26:59,850
Not one of you has the guts
to stand up alone and fight!

217
00:27:01,230 --> 00:27:03,440
Is the lorry
in case someone hits back?

218
00:27:03,730 --> 00:27:04,730
Shut up!

219
00:27:05,030 --> 00:27:07,980
Come and take me.
You'll get medals for it.

220
00:27:08,280 --> 00:27:11,120
You pick on women
and rob defenceless people.

221
00:27:11,580 --> 00:27:15,630
Don't rob the poor girl, boys.
Give her back her tomatoes.

222
00:27:55,490 --> 00:27:57,820
I'll have to do it again.

223
00:28:00,210 --> 00:28:01,240
Pigs!

224
00:28:05,300 --> 00:28:07,380
- Patient 33!
- <i>Yes, sir</i>.

225
00:28:08,140 --> 00:28:10,350
An interesting case: amnesia.

226
00:28:10,600 --> 00:28:12,930
Jewish soldier.
Been here since the war.

227
00:28:13,150 --> 00:28:14,980
He thinks it's only been weeks.

228
00:28:15,190 --> 00:28:17,190
Does he knows what's happened?

229
00:28:17,490 --> 00:28:20,610
No. His one interest
seems to be in his barbershop,

230
00:28:20,910 --> 00:28:23,070
which he believes he left
a few weeks ago.

231
00:28:23,790 --> 00:28:25,670
He'll have many surprises.

232
00:28:25,960 --> 00:28:27,210
I'm afraid so.

233
00:28:28,680 --> 00:28:30,470
- Yes?
- <i>Number 33 is gone</i>.

234
00:28:30,760 --> 00:28:32,470
He was to be examined.

235
00:28:32,770 --> 00:28:34,140
<i>But he's disappeared.</i>

236
00:28:34,520 --> 00:28:35,520
Disappeared?

237
00:28:35,730 --> 00:28:38,310
Let him go.
It isn't a serious case.

238
00:28:39,030 --> 00:28:41,150
There's little we can do for him.

239
00:30:06,100 --> 00:30:09,020
Come on, get out of here!

240
00:30:35,990 --> 00:30:37,480
What are you doing?

241
00:30:38,200 --> 00:30:38,950
I don't know.

242
00:30:39,200 --> 00:30:40,860
Leave that alone.

243
00:30:42,120 --> 00:30:44,030
- Don't be silly.
- I'm not silly!

244
00:30:44,250 --> 00:30:45,410
I appreciate that.

245
00:30:45,630 --> 00:30:47,870
When you talk to me, "Hail Hynkel"!

246
00:30:48,420 --> 00:30:49,540
Who are you?

247
00:30:51,810 --> 00:30:55,390
I'll show you who I am!
Come down to headquarters!

248
00:30:55,690 --> 00:30:56,560
That's my shop.

249
00:30:56,610 --> 00:30:58,770
I don't care if it is or not.

250
00:30:59,240 --> 00:31:02,360
Going to put up a fight, are you?
Come to headquarters.

251
00:31:04,830 --> 00:31:06,910
Let me tell you something.

252
00:31:10,300 --> 00:31:12,970
Policeman?
Arrest that man for assault.

253
00:31:13,350 --> 00:31:15,220
- Come here, you!
- Leave me alone.

254
00:31:15,430 --> 00:31:17,560
Attacking a storm trooper!

255
00:31:18,310 --> 00:31:19,640
You'll hear from my lawyer.

256
00:31:26,200 --> 00:31:27,860
He bit my finger!

257
00:32:19,340 --> 00:32:21,630
Sorry, I didn't mean to hit you.

258
00:32:21,930 --> 00:32:23,550
I enjoyed that.

259
00:32:23,970 --> 00:32:25,680
But you'd better beat it.

260
00:32:25,980 --> 00:32:27,770
- I'll call a policeman.
- No!

261
00:32:27,980 --> 00:32:29,720
- Why not?
- Are you crazy?

262
00:32:30,070 --> 00:32:31,100
More are coming!

263
00:32:31,570 --> 00:32:33,280
- More what?
- Wait!

264
00:32:39,920 --> 00:32:41,080
Come in here.

265
00:32:44,380 --> 00:32:47,090
What's wrong with you?
Don't be foolhardy.

266
00:32:56,450 --> 00:32:58,570
What's this? Who hit you?

267
00:32:59,120 --> 00:33:00,830
I think it was a gang.

268
00:33:01,120 --> 00:33:04,990
You'd better get fixed up.
We'll investigate later.

269
00:33:05,300 --> 00:33:06,580
What time is it?

270
00:33:27,840 --> 00:33:29,630
All right, they've gone.

271
00:33:29,920 --> 00:33:34,050
Thanks, mister.
That did me a lot of good.

272
00:33:36,850 --> 00:33:39,010
You've sure got some nerve.

273
00:33:39,310 --> 00:33:41,520
We should all fight back.

274
00:33:42,070 --> 00:33:45,360
We can't fight alone,
but we can lick 'em together.

275
00:33:47,120 --> 00:33:48,950
We didn't do so bad.

276
00:34:10,080 --> 00:34:12,950
You're the barber,
who was in hospital!

277
00:34:13,250 --> 00:34:15,240
Mr. Jaeckel has talked about you.

278
00:34:15,550 --> 00:34:17,500
We didn't think you'd come back.

279
00:34:19,390 --> 00:34:21,590
The storm troopers
will be after you.

280
00:34:23,180 --> 00:34:26,470
You'd better hide.
I'll get the key to the cellar.

281
00:34:34,660 --> 00:34:36,660
- Is this the man?
- That's him.

282
00:34:37,330 --> 00:34:38,530
Hail Hynkel!

283
00:34:39,170 --> 00:34:40,170
Who's he?

284
00:34:40,880 --> 00:34:43,550
Don't fool with me. Hail Hynkel!

285
00:34:45,390 --> 00:34:46,170
Your hands.

286
00:34:46,390 --> 00:34:49,520
Just a moment. Not here.
Bring him outside.

287
00:34:53,530 --> 00:34:56,070
First you'll finish this.
Here.

288
00:34:58,290 --> 00:34:59,620
Go on, paint that!

289
00:35:39,440 --> 00:35:43,830
Wait a minute, boys.
I've got a bright idea.

290
00:35:59,980 --> 00:36:01,360
Commander Schultz!

291
00:36:07,700 --> 00:36:09,030
First in command.

292
00:36:12,840 --> 00:36:14,040
Second in command.

293
00:36:17,100 --> 00:36:18,340
Oh, never mind. You!

294
00:36:19,100 --> 00:36:21,590
Who told you
to hang people from lampposts?

295
00:36:22,650 --> 00:36:24,980
What was the trouble?

296
00:36:25,280 --> 00:36:26,860
A Jew attacking storm troopers.

297
00:36:27,160 --> 00:36:28,950
- Where is he?
- There.

298
00:36:29,280 --> 00:36:30,700
Break ranks.

299
00:36:33,290 --> 00:36:36,040
So there you are. Stand him up.

300
00:36:36,920 --> 00:36:38,250
Get up.

301
00:36:44,310 --> 00:36:47,270
You?
Don't you remember me?

302
00:36:48,650 --> 00:36:51,030
- You saved my life.
- Me?

303
00:36:51,660 --> 00:36:55,110
Strange. And I always thought
of you as an Aryan.

304
00:36:55,540 --> 00:36:56,820
I'm a vegetarian.

305
00:36:57,130 --> 00:37:00,460
Don't you remember?
We got away in my plane.

306
00:37:00,670 --> 00:37:01,920
Plane?

307
00:37:02,130 --> 00:37:03,840
Then we crashed.

308
00:37:11,150 --> 00:37:12,690
Now I remember.

309
00:37:14,490 --> 00:37:15,570
Well, how are you?

310
00:37:15,830 --> 00:37:16,740
What's my friend done?

311
00:37:17,040 --> 00:37:19,200
He resisted my men
painting his windows.

312
00:37:19,540 --> 00:37:21,450
Any brave man would resist.

313
00:37:21,710 --> 00:37:22,990
I'm sorry for this.

314
00:37:23,760 --> 00:37:24,710
No harm.

315
00:37:24,970 --> 00:37:27,920
In future you will not
be molested again.

316
00:37:28,430 --> 00:37:31,100
If you or your friends
ever need help...

317
00:37:33,940 --> 00:37:35,110
Who did that?

318
00:37:37,160 --> 00:37:38,570
One of my friends.

319
00:37:47,970 --> 00:37:50,420
<i>Hynkel's palace was the centre</i>

320
00:37:50,720 --> 00:37:53,390
<i>of the world's
greatest war machine.</i>

321
00:37:53,690 --> 00:37:56,310
<i>Behind it
was the dynamic Adenoid Hynkel,</i>

322
00:37:56,610 --> 00:37:58,600
<i>whose genius ran the nation,</i>

323
00:37:58,900 --> 00:38:02,820
<i>whose ceaseless activity kept him
occupied every moment of the day.</i>

324
00:38:30,580 --> 00:38:32,040
<i>Marshal Herring is waiting.</i>

325
00:38:32,340 --> 00:38:33,250
Enough!

326
00:38:37,140 --> 00:38:39,550
I believe we've got something now.

327
00:38:39,850 --> 00:38:43,100
A bulletproof uniform.
The material is as light as silk.

328
00:38:43,320 --> 00:38:44,060
Where?

329
00:38:44,280 --> 00:38:48,030
I've arranged for a demonstration.
It will only take two minutes.

330
00:38:49,240 --> 00:38:50,820
I can spare one.

331
00:38:55,250 --> 00:38:56,750
Professor Herr Kibitzen.

332
00:38:57,880 --> 00:39:01,420
Actions speak louder than words.
A bulletproof uniform.

333
00:39:01,720 --> 00:39:04,100
One hundred percent perfect.

334
00:39:05,810 --> 00:39:07,060
Shoot!

335
00:39:12,790 --> 00:39:14,330
Far from perfect.

336
00:39:56,990 --> 00:39:59,030
- Where's my secretary?
- In the outer office.

337
00:39:59,240 --> 00:40:00,190
Call her.

338
00:40:13,270 --> 00:40:14,510
Take a letter.

339
00:40:41,070 --> 00:40:44,400
<i>Herring here in the tower room.
We've got something marvellous.</i>

340
00:40:44,700 --> 00:40:46,190
I shall be up.

341
00:41:03,570 --> 00:41:06,440
A parachute.
The most compact in the world.

342
00:41:06,740 --> 00:41:07,820
Worn like a hat.

343
00:41:10,410 --> 00:41:11,990
It will open in 25 feet.

344
00:41:12,460 --> 00:41:14,330
Demonstrate, professor.

345
00:41:34,200 --> 00:41:37,490
Herring,
why do you waste my time like this?

346
00:41:49,360 --> 00:41:50,850
Send Garbitsch here.

347
00:42:02,130 --> 00:42:03,590
<i>Herr Garbitsch is waiting.</i>

348
00:42:03,880 --> 00:42:05,080
Enough!

349
00:42:10,440 --> 00:42:12,640
What's the meaning of this?

350
00:42:12,940 --> 00:42:16,230
25 million for prison camps?
We need to manufacture munitions.

351
00:42:16,530 --> 00:42:18,860
- We've made a few arrests.
- How many?

352
00:42:19,080 --> 00:42:20,650
Five or ten thousand...

353
00:42:20,950 --> 00:42:21,900
a day.

354
00:42:22,290 --> 00:42:24,370
- A day?
- Just a few dissenters.

355
00:42:24,590 --> 00:42:25,420
Dissenting about?

356
00:42:25,710 --> 00:42:27,540
Working hours, wage cuts,

357
00:42:27,840 --> 00:42:31,090
the synthetic food, the quality
of the sawdust in the bread.

358
00:42:31,600 --> 00:42:35,180
What more do they want?
It's from the finest lumber!

359
00:42:37,730 --> 00:42:41,980
Nevertheless, the people
are overworked. They need diversion.

360
00:42:42,280 --> 00:42:43,360
The people, bah!

361
00:42:43,660 --> 00:42:46,870
We might go further with the Jews.
Burn some of their houses.

362
00:42:47,210 --> 00:42:49,500
An assault on the ghetto.

363
00:42:49,800 --> 00:42:53,960
Something more dramatic. When can
we be ready to invade Osterlich?

364
00:42:54,260 --> 00:42:55,210
Three months.

365
00:42:55,470 --> 00:42:58,810
I can't wait.
Napaloni's army might invade first.

366
00:42:59,110 --> 00:43:00,220
We must strike now.

367
00:43:00,690 --> 00:43:02,320
We'll require foreign capital.

368
00:43:02,780 --> 00:43:03,610
Borrow it!

369
00:43:03,950 --> 00:43:05,230
The bankers have refused.

370
00:43:05,450 --> 00:43:08,160
One man
might make us a loan: Epstein.

371
00:43:08,670 --> 00:43:11,790
- Epstein? He's a Jew, isn't he?
- Yes.

372
00:43:12,840 --> 00:43:15,960
Well, let's be big about it.
We'll borrow from Epstein.

373
00:43:17,510 --> 00:43:20,600
It might be difficult in view
of our policy towards his people.

374
00:43:20,810 --> 00:43:23,190
Then we'll change our policy.

375
00:43:23,440 --> 00:43:26,860
Tell Schultz all persecution
of the Jews must cease.

376
00:43:27,070 --> 00:43:30,160
At least
till we've negotiated this loan.

377
00:43:36,510 --> 00:43:40,420
I don't understand it.
The whole ghetto is so quiet.

378
00:43:40,720 --> 00:43:43,560
You can't imagine
what was going on.

379
00:43:43,890 --> 00:43:46,020
This Hynkel business.

380
00:43:46,440 --> 00:43:50,110
You weren't here, you were
in the hospital, unconscious.

381
00:43:50,410 --> 00:43:53,660
You don't appreciate
what a good time you were having.

382
00:43:55,210 --> 00:43:58,290
If things get worse
we can go to Osterlich.

383
00:43:58,540 --> 00:44:00,250
That's still free.

384
00:44:00,670 --> 00:44:03,130
Sooner or later we'll have to go.

385
00:44:04,180 --> 00:44:07,220
Anyway, it's nice to see you back.

386
00:44:07,810 --> 00:44:10,060
It's like the old days again, eh?

387
00:44:10,900 --> 00:44:12,180
How's business?

388
00:44:12,490 --> 00:44:14,360
Very slow.

389
00:44:15,780 --> 00:44:17,780
The men are in concentration camp.

390
00:44:19,120 --> 00:44:20,830
You should fix up the women.

391
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:23,750
The beauty parlour business.

392
00:44:25,090 --> 00:44:26,750
Know anything about it?

393
00:44:31,860 --> 00:44:35,140
You can learn.
You can practise on Hannah.

394
00:44:38,410 --> 00:44:41,950
Hannah, get in that chair,
we'll make you look beautiful.

395
00:44:42,250 --> 00:44:43,660
What for?

396
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:46,290
He's going to practise on you.

397
00:44:49,510 --> 00:44:51,340
Not with mud on my face?

398
00:44:51,850 --> 00:44:53,640
No, we'll take some off.

399
00:44:56,060 --> 00:44:57,690
Make me look beautiful?

400
00:44:57,900 --> 00:45:00,690
Sure.
He can't make you look any worse!

401
00:45:04,410 --> 00:45:05,910
Mrs. Shoemaker's laundry!

402
00:45:06,120 --> 00:45:09,410
I'll give it to her.
You sit here and enjoy yourself.

403
00:45:11,430 --> 00:45:14,630
I know.
I've seen you making eyes.

404
00:45:17,810 --> 00:45:20,390
Don't pay any attention to him.

405
00:45:22,990 --> 00:45:25,440
I like your shop
since it's fixed up.

406
00:45:26,870 --> 00:45:30,820
I wish I had a business like this.
There's no future in housework.

407
00:45:31,500 --> 00:45:35,170
Maybe if I save my money
I can have a barbershop some day.

408
00:45:35,430 --> 00:45:39,640
But I can never save.
Money slips through my fingers.

409
00:45:40,270 --> 00:45:43,270
I've always lived
up to every penny I've earned.

410
00:45:43,650 --> 00:45:47,230
Why shouldn't I? You're here today
and gone tomorrow.

411
00:45:49,030 --> 00:45:50,490
Do you believe in God?

412
00:45:51,210 --> 00:45:54,740
I do. But if there wasn't one,
would you live any different?

413
00:45:55,250 --> 00:45:56,420
I wouldn't.

414
00:45:56,710 --> 00:45:59,840
Life could be wonderful
if people'd leave you alone.

415
00:46:00,350 --> 00:46:02,220
Things are looking brighter now.

416
00:46:02,560 --> 00:46:05,400
Maybe because of you saving Schultz.

417
00:46:06,150 --> 00:46:08,360
Funny how they've left us alone.

418
00:46:08,900 --> 00:46:09,980
Too good to be true.

419
00:46:17,380 --> 00:46:20,330
Do you ever daydream?
I do.

420
00:46:21,590 --> 00:46:25,590
That's the only time
I'm really happy: dreaming.

421
00:46:29,480 --> 00:46:31,810
Sometimes I get so carried away
I don't know what I'm doing.

422
00:46:32,030 --> 00:46:33,650
Aren't you like that?

423
00:46:35,530 --> 00:46:37,530
We're very much alike.

424
00:46:37,830 --> 00:46:39,820
- Both absent-minded.
- You think so?

425
00:46:45,010 --> 00:46:46,750
I like absent-minded people.

426
00:46:52,400 --> 00:46:55,980
Like the man who put his watch
in boiling water and held the egg!

427
00:47:04,420 --> 00:47:07,750
All great men are absent-minded.
It's a sign you're smart.

428
00:47:09,220 --> 00:47:11,100
My folks didn't think so.

429
00:47:14,270 --> 00:47:17,270
You have an excuse.
You were injured in the war.

430
00:47:17,940 --> 00:47:19,610
I was born that way.

431
00:47:27,580 --> 00:47:30,290
I wonder
why women never grow whiskers.

432
00:47:39,610 --> 00:47:41,600
Isn't that foolish of me?

433
00:47:41,900 --> 00:47:44,660
I could kick myself in the shins,
I could...

434
00:47:45,870 --> 00:47:47,330
I'll give you a shampoo.

435
00:48:03,860 --> 00:48:05,820
Ain't I cute?

436
00:48:08,070 --> 00:48:09,270
How did you do it?

437
00:48:11,460 --> 00:48:13,370
You should try it on yourself.

438
00:48:14,420 --> 00:48:16,540
Fixed up, you'd look handsome.

439
00:48:21,930 --> 00:48:24,810
Four pecks a pound, new potatoes!

440
00:48:25,020 --> 00:48:27,860
The potato man! I have to go.

441
00:48:42,300 --> 00:48:43,800
Take it easy there.

442
00:48:45,600 --> 00:48:47,180
Did you hurt yourself?

443
00:48:53,280 --> 00:48:55,900
- Careful next time.
- Here's another one.

444
00:48:59,330 --> 00:49:00,360
How do you do?

445
00:49:09,230 --> 00:49:12,890
Something's happened.
The storm troopers helped me up.

446
00:49:13,650 --> 00:49:15,810
How wonderful
if they stopped hating us,

447
00:49:16,110 --> 00:49:19,570
if they let us go about our business
like we used to.

448
00:49:20,040 --> 00:49:23,460
How wonderful if we didn't have
to go to another country.

449
00:49:23,750 --> 00:49:25,130
I don't want to go.

450
00:49:25,420 --> 00:49:28,590
With all the persecution,
I still love it here.

451
00:49:28,930 --> 00:49:30,640
Perhaps we don't have to go.

452
00:49:31,470 --> 00:49:35,140
Wouldn't it be wonderful if they'd
let us live and be happy again?

453
00:50:12,760 --> 00:50:13,630
Full stop.

454
00:50:43,310 --> 00:50:45,520
Nothing works!
Not even a sharp pencil.

455
00:50:45,810 --> 00:50:49,150
I'm surrounded by incompetent,
stupid, sterile stenographers.

456
00:50:49,490 --> 00:50:50,400
I'll get you a pen.

457
00:50:50,700 --> 00:50:53,020
Don't bother! I won't send it.

458
00:50:54,160 --> 00:50:55,540
Get out, get out!

459
00:51:01,300 --> 00:51:05,930
We've just discovered
the most wonderful poison gas.

460
00:51:07,310 --> 00:51:09,640
It will kill everybody...

461
00:51:09,940 --> 00:51:11,400
All right. Later.

462
00:51:12,190 --> 00:51:13,940
<i>B76 to see Herr Herring.</i>

463
00:51:15,030 --> 00:51:17,530
A lady. My secret agent.

464
00:51:17,960 --> 00:51:20,530
Your secret agent?
Tell her to come here.

465
00:51:20,750 --> 00:51:23,000
Have B76 come right in.

466
00:51:24,420 --> 00:51:25,970
Any news from Epstein?

467
00:51:26,220 --> 00:51:29,760
Our agent reports that all
the board of directors are Aryans.

468
00:51:30,060 --> 00:51:32,060
- The loan's bound to go through.
- Good.

469
00:51:41,500 --> 00:51:43,210
A strike at the arms factory.

470
00:51:43,500 --> 00:51:45,500
- The leader?
- Five of them.

471
00:51:45,920 --> 00:51:48,680
- Have them shot.
- They were.

472
00:51:51,850 --> 00:51:53,430
How many were going to strike?

473
00:51:53,730 --> 00:51:55,220
Three thousand of them.

474
00:51:55,480 --> 00:51:58,400
Have them all shot.
I don't want dissatisfied workers.

475
00:51:58,690 --> 00:52:00,690
These men are skilled craftsmen.

476
00:52:00,990 --> 00:52:03,700
Let's train others first,
then shoot them!

477
00:52:04,000 --> 00:52:05,370
Cannot afford to be lenient.

478
00:52:05,710 --> 00:52:08,000
The rhythm of production
will be affected.

479
00:52:08,290 --> 00:52:10,870
Rhythm...
All right, have your rhythm.

480
00:52:11,260 --> 00:52:14,840
Spare the strikers and permit them
to return to work.

481
00:52:15,270 --> 00:52:17,430
But mark them for future reference.

482
00:52:18,230 --> 00:52:21,320
That's my department.
I'll attend to that. This way.

483
00:52:26,370 --> 00:52:30,040
The strike leaders are all
brunettes. Not one blond.

484
00:52:30,330 --> 00:52:32,210
Troublemakers!
Worse than Jews.

485
00:52:32,500 --> 00:52:34,710
- Then wipe them out!
- "Doucement".

486
00:52:34,930 --> 00:52:38,760
We'll get rid of the Jews first,
then concentrate on the brunettes.

487
00:52:39,060 --> 00:52:42,560
We shall never have peace
till we have a pure Aryan race.

488
00:52:42,810 --> 00:52:46,900
How wonderful! Tomainia,
a nation of blue-eyed blonds.

489
00:52:47,200 --> 00:52:49,610
Why not
a blond Europe, Asia, America?

490
00:52:50,290 --> 00:52:52,830
- And a brunette dictator.
- Of the world!

491
00:52:53,040 --> 00:52:54,160
Why not?

492
00:52:54,840 --> 00:52:58,840
<i>Aut Caesar aut nullus</i>.
The world's effete, worn out, afraid.

493
00:52:59,090 --> 00:53:00,970
No nation would dare oppose you.

494
00:53:01,390 --> 00:53:02,340
Dictator of the World!

495
00:53:02,640 --> 00:53:06,940
It's your destiny. We'll kill off
the Jews, wipe out the brunettes,

496
00:53:07,230 --> 00:53:09,770
then will come forth
a pure Aryan race.

497
00:53:10,070 --> 00:53:11,240
Beautiful blond Aryans.

498
00:53:11,530 --> 00:53:14,790
They will love you,
they will worship you as a god.

499
00:53:15,080 --> 00:53:16,710
No, you mustn't say it.

500
00:53:20,880 --> 00:53:22,840
You make me afraid of myself.

501
00:53:31,150 --> 00:53:33,110
Dictator of the World!

502
00:53:33,360 --> 00:53:37,150
We'll invade Osterlich first.
After that we can bluff.

503
00:53:37,460 --> 00:53:39,160
The nations will capitulate.

504
00:53:39,460 --> 00:53:42,080
The world will be under your thumb.

505
00:53:42,630 --> 00:53:45,420
Leave me! I want to be alone.

506
00:54:16,110 --> 00:54:19,030
<i>Aut Caesar aut nullus.</i>

507
00:54:19,700 --> 00:54:22,070
Emperor of the World!

508
00:54:26,040 --> 00:54:27,580
My world.

509
00:56:19,370 --> 00:56:21,490
<i>The happy hour programme.</i>

510
00:56:21,790 --> 00:56:24,280
<i>Work with the rhythm of music.</i>

511
00:56:24,590 --> 00:56:28,170
<i>Our next selection: Brahms'
Hungarian Dance number five.</i>

512
00:58:16,830 --> 00:58:18,620
Fifteen cents, please.

513
00:58:26,220 --> 00:58:27,880
<i>Happy hour signing off.</i>

514
00:58:28,180 --> 00:58:30,560
<i>At six, Adenoid Hynkel will address</i>

515
00:58:30,850 --> 00:58:33,100
<i>the children of the double-cross.</i>

516
00:58:33,360 --> 00:58:35,850
It seems like the old days again.

517
00:58:36,150 --> 00:58:38,030
How long is it going to last?

518
00:58:38,280 --> 00:58:39,280
In the papers

519
00:58:39,580 --> 00:58:43,360
it's rumoured that Hynkel's going
to give the Jews back their rights.

520
00:58:43,670 --> 00:58:44,620
Maybe.

521
00:58:45,170 --> 00:58:46,330
What do you want?

522
00:58:46,630 --> 00:58:50,170
Business is much better.
Nobody interferes with us any more.

523
00:58:50,430 --> 00:58:52,390
Doesn't that make you feel good?

524
00:58:54,310 --> 00:58:55,890
The trouble, Mr. Jaeckel,

525
00:58:56,190 --> 00:58:59,530
is you're so used to bad times,
you're unhappy without them.

526
00:59:00,820 --> 00:59:04,160
Get my Sunday shoes.
They're on the windowsill.

527
00:59:05,040 --> 00:59:06,290
I can't find the shawl.

528
00:59:06,540 --> 00:59:07,870
I've got a shawl.

529
00:59:08,170 --> 00:59:09,420
What's going on?

530
00:59:09,710 --> 00:59:12,550
They're dressing Hannah up
to go out.

531
00:59:12,760 --> 00:59:14,220
Is that so?

532
00:59:14,720 --> 00:59:15,920
She's got a beau.

533
00:59:16,140 --> 00:59:17,890
- Who is it?
- The barber.

534
00:59:18,940 --> 00:59:21,180
Now, turn around.

535
00:59:22,990 --> 00:59:25,940
- My dear! Those hands!
- What's the matter with them?

536
00:59:26,160 --> 00:59:28,400
Those calluses. They're so rough.

537
00:59:28,710 --> 00:59:29,870
Maybe I better not go.

538
00:59:30,170 --> 00:59:33,370
Don't be foolish.
He knows you do housework.

539
00:59:33,670 --> 00:59:36,300
Wait! I'll get a pair of mittens.

540
00:59:43,900 --> 00:59:44,900
See if he's ready.

541
00:59:59,600 --> 01:00:03,130
Not yet. He's polishing
a bald man's head.

542
01:00:10,030 --> 01:00:13,400
Bad news. The invasion of Osterlich
will have to be delayed.

543
01:00:13,660 --> 01:00:17,000
- What?
- Epstein refuses to lend the money.

544
01:00:19,170 --> 01:00:21,210
Epstein refuses, eh?

545
01:00:25,310 --> 01:00:26,420
Send for Schultz.

546
01:00:29,900 --> 01:00:31,480
Epstein refuses.

547
01:00:36,120 --> 01:00:37,070
What did he say?

548
01:00:37,330 --> 01:00:39,240
He complained of the persecution

549
01:00:39,500 --> 01:00:43,170
and said he wouldn't have any
dealings with a mediaeval maniac.

550
01:00:43,380 --> 01:00:46,630
He'll deal with a mediaeval maniac
more than he thinks!

551
01:00:49,730 --> 01:00:52,650
First I shall deal with his people.

552
01:00:53,440 --> 01:00:56,020
- Your Excellency?
- Call out the storm troopers.

553
01:00:56,360 --> 01:00:59,320
A little mediaeval entertainment
in the ghetto!

554
01:00:59,660 --> 01:01:02,420
At such a time
I think it ill-advised.

555
01:01:03,540 --> 01:01:06,300
Such demonstrations
demoralise the country.

556
01:01:06,550 --> 01:01:08,090
Indeed?

557
01:01:09,430 --> 01:01:12,140
Since when
do you care about the ghetto?

558
01:01:12,390 --> 01:01:15,650
I speak in the interests of our party
and the cause of humanity.

559
01:01:19,280 --> 01:01:20,940
You need a holiday.

560
01:01:21,990 --> 01:01:23,160
Fresh air.

561
01:01:26,040 --> 01:01:28,450
A little outdoor exercise.

562
01:01:29,920 --> 01:01:32,170
I'll send you
to a concentration camp.

563
01:01:35,350 --> 01:01:37,260
Place Schultz under arrest.

564
01:01:37,560 --> 01:01:40,900
Very well, but remember my words.
Your cause is doomed to failure

565
01:01:41,190 --> 01:01:44,480
because it is built on the stupid
persecution of innocent people.

566
01:01:44,740 --> 01:01:48,660
Your policy is worse than a crime.
It's a tragic blunder.

567
01:01:49,130 --> 01:01:51,290
Traitor! Traitor!

568
01:01:52,590 --> 01:01:54,550
You're a double-dyed democrat!

569
01:02:17,630 --> 01:02:21,250
Schultz, why have you forsaken me?

570
01:02:33,700 --> 01:02:36,830
Excellency,
here are the notes for your speech.

571
01:02:49,520 --> 01:02:50,940
I'll not need them.

572
01:02:51,360 --> 01:02:55,200
What I say will not be directed
to the children of the double-cross

573
01:02:55,410 --> 01:02:58,860
but to the children of Israel!

574
01:03:50,970 --> 01:03:54,300
That Hynkel isn't such a bad fellow
after all.

575
01:03:54,560 --> 01:03:56,050
Most amusing.

576
01:03:56,560 --> 01:03:59,020
Get a Hynkel badge!
A Hynkel badge!

577
01:03:59,270 --> 01:04:00,730
A fine photo on each!

578
01:04:49,360 --> 01:04:50,940
- We'd better go home.
- Yeah.

579
01:04:52,330 --> 01:04:53,530
Let's hurry.

580
01:04:53,790 --> 01:04:54,740
Wait a minute.

581
01:05:46,420 --> 01:05:47,500
What's that?

582
01:05:48,800 --> 01:05:50,210
Turn off the radio.

583
01:05:56,650 --> 01:05:58,190
The storm troopers!

584
01:06:14,810 --> 01:06:16,470
- Bar that door!
- Get some water!

585
01:06:23,110 --> 01:06:26,780
Get the women and children upstairs.
Lock all the doors.

586
01:06:29,790 --> 01:06:32,290
You men, stay right here.

587
01:06:32,590 --> 01:06:34,550
We've got to make a stand.

588
01:06:35,220 --> 01:06:38,010
We might as well die
as live like this.

589
01:06:44,360 --> 01:06:48,150
Wait a minute.
We have a social call to make here.

590
01:06:59,180 --> 01:07:00,420
Wait a minute!

591
01:07:02,770 --> 01:07:06,940
Schultz gave strict orders
not to molest anyone in this court.

592
01:07:07,320 --> 01:07:08,730
These Jews attacked us.

593
01:07:09,110 --> 01:07:10,030
I don't care.

594
01:07:10,240 --> 01:07:11,780
Orders were to keep out.

595
01:07:14,040 --> 01:07:15,500
You saw that!

596
01:07:15,750 --> 01:07:18,040
I can't help it. Schultz's orders.

597
01:07:18,250 --> 01:07:19,710
Let's get going.

598
01:07:38,330 --> 01:07:41,090
Orders or not,
I'm going to get that girl.

599
01:07:42,880 --> 01:07:43,710
Out!

600
01:08:02,630 --> 01:08:04,120
Schultz arrested!

601
01:08:04,420 --> 01:08:07,540
Hear that?
He's arrested Commander Schultz.

602
01:08:11,770 --> 01:08:15,550
- A Jew corrupted our commander.
- Let's kill the louse!

603
01:08:15,860 --> 01:08:19,520
Schultz is accused of treason,
and you know why.

604
01:08:19,950 --> 01:08:22,900
Schultz was a friend of that barber.

605
01:08:23,200 --> 01:08:25,830
Let's get the barber!
We want the barber!

606
01:08:28,090 --> 01:08:29,920
It's the storm troopers!

607
01:08:30,260 --> 01:08:32,300
- Get on the roof.
- No.

608
01:08:32,510 --> 01:08:34,840
- They'll kill you!
- I'll fight.

609
01:08:35,140 --> 01:08:38,760
Don't be a fool, you'll
be murdered. Get on the roof.

610
01:08:46,910 --> 01:08:50,250
All right, here we are.
Smash in the door!

611
01:08:53,380 --> 01:08:56,250
Come on,
we'll give the barber a haircut!

612
01:09:01,480 --> 01:09:03,020
Where are the bombs?

613
01:09:22,140 --> 01:09:23,970
There goes the barbershop!

614
01:09:26,900 --> 01:09:29,110
Never mind. We can start again.

615
01:09:29,360 --> 01:09:32,200
We can go to Osterlich.
That's still free.

616
01:09:32,660 --> 01:09:34,790
Mr. Jaeckel says it's beautiful.

617
01:09:35,080 --> 01:09:38,120
Wonderful green fields,
and they grow apples and grapes.

618
01:09:38,840 --> 01:09:41,410
His brother's got a vineyard.

619
01:09:41,720 --> 01:09:44,560
Mr. Jaeckel
said he'd take me with him.

620
01:09:45,180 --> 01:09:46,850
Now we can all go together.

621
01:09:47,810 --> 01:09:50,310
It'll be wonderful
living in the country,

622
01:09:51,030 --> 01:09:53,780
much better than a smoky old city.

623
01:09:54,830 --> 01:09:58,110
And if we work hard and
don't eat much, we can save money

624
01:09:59,120 --> 01:10:00,790
and buy a chicken farm.

625
01:10:02,380 --> 01:10:04,620
There's money
to be made in chickens.

626
01:10:27,300 --> 01:10:28,960
Look at that star!

627
01:10:31,220 --> 01:10:32,880
Isn't it beautiful!

628
01:10:36,530 --> 01:10:40,030
Hynkel with all his power
can never touch that.

629
01:10:42,830 --> 01:10:44,870
All right, the coast is clear.

630
01:10:45,120 --> 01:10:48,250
Commander Schultz escaped.
He's hiding in my cellar.

631
01:10:49,380 --> 01:10:52,720
He's holding a meeting at midnight
and he wants you to be there.

632
01:10:53,060 --> 01:10:56,430
Hannah, you come and help
Mrs. Jaeckel with the supper.

633
01:10:56,640 --> 01:10:58,060
All right, I'll be down.

634
01:11:03,070 --> 01:11:07,200
I don't understand it.
This crazy midnight supper...

635
01:11:07,620 --> 01:11:10,000
What does this Schultz want of us?

636
01:11:10,630 --> 01:11:13,580
- He wants us to blow up the palace.
- What?

637
01:11:14,430 --> 01:11:17,600
We Jewish people shouldn't
get mixed up in such a business.

638
01:11:17,850 --> 01:11:21,300
I know it but Schultz
has them all hypnotised.

639
01:11:21,610 --> 01:11:24,860
- I knew he was up to some mischief.
- Sure he is.

640
01:11:26,530 --> 01:11:30,910
I found him putting a coin
in one of your puddings.

641
01:11:33,750 --> 01:11:37,090
Don't worry, I've fixed everything.
Wait and see.

642
01:11:37,550 --> 01:11:41,600
Gentlemen, may I claim
your indulgence for a moment?

643
01:11:42,060 --> 01:11:46,390
We are here tonight
to rid the country of a tyrant.

644
01:11:47,240 --> 01:11:50,020
In order to carry this out
one of us must die.

645
01:11:53,290 --> 01:11:56,240
In ancient times the Aryan tribe
of the Langobardians

646
01:11:56,540 --> 01:11:59,710
made human sacrifice
to the god Thor.

647
01:12:00,930 --> 01:12:03,760
At a feast
by lottery the victim was chosen.

648
01:12:04,100 --> 01:12:07,720
Tonight, at this feast,
one of you will be chosen.

649
01:12:11,610 --> 01:12:13,490
Each man will receive a pudding.

650
01:12:13,870 --> 01:12:16,030
Concealed in one of these is a coin.

651
01:12:16,330 --> 01:12:19,280
Whoever gets it
must give up his life

652
01:12:19,580 --> 01:12:23,830
but he will join the long line
of history's noble martyrs

653
01:12:24,380 --> 01:12:28,170
and will rid his country
of a tyrant.

654
01:12:39,290 --> 01:12:41,740
I know that it is the wish
of all of us

655
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:44,870
to be chosen this night
to die for Tomainia.

656
01:12:45,840 --> 01:12:49,710
Much as I should like to participate
in this ordeal, I cannot...

657
01:12:50,310 --> 01:12:51,550
Why?

658
01:12:54,900 --> 01:12:57,570
Don't you understand?
He's too well known.

659
01:12:57,820 --> 01:12:59,900
It must be somebody like us.

660
01:13:00,570 --> 01:13:02,120
I can't see it like that.

661
01:13:02,450 --> 01:13:06,200
It is a question of my honour.
It is very embarrassing.

662
01:13:07,790 --> 01:13:10,960
Commander Schultz,
I apologise for my friend.

663
01:13:11,300 --> 01:13:14,510
Let me say, on behalf
of myself and the others,

664
01:13:14,810 --> 01:13:18,430
that we consider it a great
privilege to die for our country.

665
01:13:19,440 --> 01:13:20,470
Very well, then.

666
01:13:20,690 --> 01:13:24,940
Gentlemen, I shall now retire
until fate has chosen the liberator.

667
01:13:28,290 --> 01:13:30,500
Until then... Hail Hynk...

668
01:13:30,790 --> 01:13:32,250
What am I saying?

669
01:13:33,170 --> 01:13:37,390
Gentlemen,
we have pledged our honour.

670
01:13:38,310 --> 01:13:39,090
Proceed!

671
01:16:45,810 --> 01:16:48,730
Gentlemen, the coin is here!

672
01:16:54,830 --> 01:16:56,370
What's the meaning of this?

673
01:16:56,950 --> 01:16:58,070
Somebody made a fool of us.

674
01:16:58,330 --> 01:17:00,160
- I did.
- What?

675
01:17:00,500 --> 01:17:02,580
I put a coin in every pudding.

676
01:17:07,310 --> 01:17:10,480
Blowing up palaces
and wanting to kill people!

677
01:17:10,770 --> 01:17:12,650
We're in enough trouble!

678
01:17:13,990 --> 01:17:17,190
Hannah's right.
We've all been foolish.

679
01:17:17,530 --> 01:17:20,820
Our place is at home,
looking after our own affairs.

680
01:17:43,700 --> 01:17:46,660
The papers say
Schultz may be in the ghetto.

681
01:17:46,960 --> 01:17:49,170
Here, read it for yourself.

682
01:17:52,390 --> 01:17:54,210
Hannah, read that.

683
01:17:54,470 --> 01:17:57,560
"Mystery surrounds the disappearance
of ex-Commander Schultz.

684
01:17:57,770 --> 01:18:01,360
"At police HQ it was believed
he may be hiding in the ghetto.

685
01:18:01,610 --> 01:18:05,150
"A certain Jewish barber,
reported to be a friend of Schultz,

686
01:18:05,410 --> 01:18:07,070
"is wanted for questioning."

687
01:18:07,330 --> 01:18:08,160
Me?

688
01:18:08,370 --> 01:18:10,780
Only for questioning.
Not too serious.

689
01:18:11,250 --> 01:18:15,420
Meyerberg was only wanted for
questioning. We never saw him again.

690
01:18:25,820 --> 01:18:27,950
- Who is it?
- It's me, Mr. Mann.

691
01:18:36,510 --> 01:18:40,260
Did you hear what they're saying
about Schultz hiding in the ghetto?

692
01:18:40,470 --> 01:18:41,470
I know, I know.

693
01:18:41,680 --> 01:18:45,220
Don't you think it's serious
if they find him in the house?

694
01:18:47,320 --> 01:18:48,150
Don't you realise

695
01:18:48,400 --> 01:18:50,200
there are spies everywhere!

696
01:18:50,410 --> 01:18:51,610
Spies?

697
01:18:56,130 --> 01:18:57,210
What's the matter?

698
01:18:57,500 --> 01:18:59,880
He's wanted for questioning.

699
01:19:02,100 --> 01:19:03,210
Where's the Commander?

700
01:19:03,600 --> 01:19:05,180
In the next room.

701
01:19:05,890 --> 01:19:09,100
If Commander Schultz
is found in this house,

702
01:19:09,440 --> 01:19:11,270
we'll all go
to a concentration camp

703
01:19:11,530 --> 01:19:13,570
and have our heads cut off, too!

704
01:19:14,160 --> 01:19:15,820
Am I arguing?

705
01:19:16,120 --> 01:19:17,450
Then get rid of him.

706
01:19:17,660 --> 01:19:19,210
You can't throw him out.

707
01:19:19,420 --> 01:19:21,000
Of course not.

708
01:19:21,300 --> 01:19:25,800
But I'd like to know how long
he's going to stay here.

709
01:19:26,220 --> 01:19:28,680
Your breakfast is on the table.

710
01:19:30,270 --> 01:19:33,230
Thank you. I have breakfast
waiting at home.

711
01:19:34,740 --> 01:19:37,030
Search every house.

712
01:19:41,750 --> 01:19:44,590
- What now?
- They're looking for Schultz.

713
01:19:44,800 --> 01:19:46,870
He's in one of these houses.

714
01:19:47,180 --> 01:19:49,470
They're always looking
for somebody.

715
01:20:03,370 --> 01:20:04,750
It's me. Let me in.

716
01:20:12,140 --> 01:20:15,760
The storm troopers
are searching every house.

717
01:20:16,060 --> 01:20:17,440
Tell the Commander.

718
01:20:24,990 --> 01:20:26,450
- Did you tell him?
- Yes.

719
01:20:26,660 --> 01:20:29,200
- What is it?
- The storm troopers.

720
01:20:29,420 --> 01:20:32,040
- What?
- You'd both better get on the roof.

721
01:20:33,340 --> 01:20:35,670
We can't leave all these things.

722
01:20:35,970 --> 01:20:38,130
All of you, pack my cases.

723
01:20:40,350 --> 01:20:41,430
You pack that.

724
01:20:50,580 --> 01:20:52,080
Clear this shelf.

725
01:20:55,420 --> 01:20:57,250
Pack this and this.

726
01:20:57,510 --> 01:20:59,130
This mustn't be found.

727
01:20:59,390 --> 01:21:00,630
Open the door.

728
01:21:06,900 --> 01:21:09,440
They're here! Get up on the roof.

729
01:21:10,990 --> 01:21:12,320
Nothing left behind!

730
01:21:12,540 --> 01:21:14,580
- My golf clubs!
- The hatbox!

731
01:21:17,710 --> 01:21:19,920
- Take this.
- Come on, let's hurry!

732
01:21:20,170 --> 01:21:21,420
- Where are you going?
- With him.

733
01:21:21,720 --> 01:21:22,960
You'll see him later.

734
01:21:23,260 --> 01:21:25,390
- I'll meet you tonight.
- All right.

735
01:21:25,940 --> 01:21:27,050
Take this.

736
01:21:31,950 --> 01:21:32,900
Quick!

737
01:21:33,120 --> 01:21:35,280
Open in the name of Hynkel!

738
01:21:43,090 --> 01:21:44,470
Stop!

739
01:21:45,100 --> 01:21:47,050
Look where you are!

740
01:21:49,140 --> 01:21:51,270
I can't see, wait a moment.

741
01:21:51,730 --> 01:21:53,110
My bag!

742
01:21:53,400 --> 01:21:55,150
It's right here. Here it is.

743
01:22:02,790 --> 01:22:05,330
Don't drop the other one.

744
01:22:06,300 --> 01:22:09,010
My golf clubs, not my golf clubs!

745
01:22:09,640 --> 01:22:11,680
Come here. They'll see you.

746
01:22:14,060 --> 01:22:15,520
Quick, this way!

747
01:22:20,570 --> 01:22:22,320
Woah, steady!

748
01:22:23,200 --> 01:22:25,660
- Now be careful.
- Yes, sir.

749
01:22:26,630 --> 01:22:28,450
Lucky you didn't break your neck.

750
01:22:34,100 --> 01:22:35,560
You'll pardon me.

751
01:22:38,860 --> 01:22:39,970
I'm sorry.

752
01:22:42,360 --> 01:22:44,610
You guard the back. Wait a minute!

753
01:22:45,080 --> 01:22:47,150
I'll have to bother you again.

754
01:22:48,170 --> 01:22:49,330
There he is.

755
01:22:54,050 --> 01:22:55,630
How are you?

756
01:22:56,600 --> 01:22:57,680
So-so.

757
01:22:57,890 --> 01:22:59,440
Here's your friend.

758
01:22:59,730 --> 01:23:02,060
Your silence will be appreciated.

759
01:23:02,400 --> 01:23:03,680
Take him to the wagon.

760
01:23:18,050 --> 01:23:19,250
Where are you going?

761
01:23:19,560 --> 01:23:20,390
Smoking room.

762
01:23:20,720 --> 01:23:22,140
Come on, this way!

763
01:24:12,070 --> 01:24:13,480
Osterlich!

764
01:25:47,570 --> 01:25:50,240
I am pleased to announce
that we are at last

765
01:25:50,450 --> 01:25:52,490
ready to march on Osterlich.

766
01:25:52,870 --> 01:25:57,370
This was made possible by the genius
of Field Marshal Herring,

767
01:25:57,840 --> 01:26:00,880
upon whom I shall now pin
a token of my regard.

768
01:26:25,640 --> 01:26:27,300
Turn around. No!

769
01:26:41,290 --> 01:26:42,570
Gentlemen.

770
01:26:44,750 --> 01:26:46,300
To Field Marshal Herring!

771
01:26:47,220 --> 01:26:49,180
To the invasion of Osterlich!

772
01:27:06,040 --> 01:27:07,670
Elephant!

773
01:27:12,180 --> 01:27:13,130
Wait.

774
01:27:13,350 --> 01:27:15,590
Napaloni's army
is on the Osterlich front.

775
01:27:17,230 --> 01:27:19,560
60,000 men are on the border.

776
01:27:19,820 --> 01:27:21,100
To take Osterlich!

777
01:27:21,400 --> 01:27:22,860
I can't believe it.

778
01:27:26,250 --> 01:27:27,620
You can't believe it!

779
01:27:30,250 --> 01:27:32,130
You let him steal a march on us.

780
01:27:39,730 --> 01:27:41,640
I had the ground covered.

781
01:28:13,620 --> 01:28:16,200
Declare war on Napaloni!

782
01:28:16,710 --> 01:28:19,670
Mobilise every division
of the army and air force.

783
01:28:19,970 --> 01:28:21,430
Attack Bacteria at once!

784
01:28:21,720 --> 01:28:23,180
- But...
- Do as I tell you!

785
01:28:23,390 --> 01:28:24,470
- Madness.
- Shut up!

786
01:28:24,680 --> 01:28:25,680
Will you sign this?

787
01:28:25,940 --> 01:28:26,880
What is it?

788
01:28:27,190 --> 01:28:28,300
A declaration of war.

789
01:28:28,650 --> 01:28:30,140
Yes. A pen!

790
01:28:31,530 --> 01:28:32,650
I'll sign it.

791
01:28:38,460 --> 01:28:39,410
A pen!

792
01:28:39,630 --> 01:28:42,040
I'll sign it! Napaloni...

793
01:28:48,270 --> 01:28:50,140
- It's Napaloni.
- Wait a minute.

794
01:28:50,350 --> 01:28:51,770
Napaloni?

795
01:28:52,780 --> 01:28:53,690
You talk to him.

796
01:28:53,940 --> 01:28:54,890
What'll I say?

797
01:28:55,200 --> 01:28:57,900
Be nice, affable, pleasant.

798
01:29:01,960 --> 01:29:03,920
Well, well, how are you?

799
01:29:06,470 --> 01:29:08,920
No, he hasn't been playing much.

800
01:29:09,430 --> 01:29:11,590
You went round in 92?

801
01:29:13,480 --> 01:29:15,350
His Excellency?

802
01:29:20,530 --> 01:29:22,330
Just now he's a little hoarse.

803
01:29:23,410 --> 01:29:25,700
No, I mean he can't talk.

804
01:29:26,960 --> 01:29:28,460
May I take a message?

805
01:29:29,840 --> 01:29:32,880
He says no doubt you've heard
about Osterlich.

806
01:29:33,180 --> 01:29:34,460
He wants to discuss it.

807
01:29:34,890 --> 01:29:36,220
Ask him to come here.

808
01:29:36,560 --> 01:29:40,520
His Excellency invites you
to Tomainia to discuss the matter.

809
01:29:41,740 --> 01:29:44,450
Very well.
I'll make the arrangements.

810
01:29:46,910 --> 01:29:47,790
He's coming.

811
01:29:47,830 --> 01:29:48,910
Good.

812
01:29:49,170 --> 01:29:52,290
We'll put on the greatest military
show the world has ever known.

813
01:29:52,510 --> 01:29:56,720
Napaloni will leave
the invasion of Osterlich to me.

814
01:29:58,520 --> 01:29:59,680
And this?

815
01:29:59,900 --> 01:30:02,690
- What is it?
- Your declaration of war.

816
01:30:05,490 --> 01:30:07,030
Peace is declared!

817
01:30:10,080 --> 01:30:14,500
<i>2,975,000 eager citizens
are massed in the station square</i>

818
01:30:14,750 --> 01:30:17,050
<i>awaiting Benzino Napaloni.</i>

819
01:30:17,760 --> 01:30:20,970
<i>Entering the station is our Phooey,
ready to greet his guest.</i>

820
01:30:21,270 --> 01:30:23,260
<i>This will cement the friendship</i>

821
01:30:23,520 --> 01:30:27,650
<i>between our Phooey
and the Dictator of Bacteria.</i>

822
01:30:28,700 --> 01:30:31,820
<i>His Excellency is about to greet
the Bacterian ambassador.</i>

823
01:30:32,540 --> 01:30:34,450
How do you do?

824
01:30:35,630 --> 01:30:37,120
Garbitsch...

825
01:30:38,710 --> 01:30:40,710
See about the photography.

826
01:30:42,510 --> 01:30:45,930
Tell the press to see that
our Phooey is well photographed.

827
01:30:46,230 --> 01:30:48,390
- Not the back of his head!
- Yes, sir.

828
01:30:48,610 --> 01:30:51,230
<i>Napaloni's train
is coming into the station.</i>

829
01:30:51,490 --> 01:30:53,200
<i>From a pink and white carriage</i>

830
01:30:53,450 --> 01:30:56,070
<i>Napaloni and his wife will step out</i>

831
01:30:56,370 --> 01:30:59,460
<i>and Adenoid Hynkel will deliver
his address of welcome.</i>

832
01:31:13,780 --> 01:31:15,360
What's all this mix-up-a?

833
01:31:15,570 --> 01:31:17,400
They've gone too far.

834
01:31:18,950 --> 01:31:20,280
At ease!

835
01:31:20,500 --> 01:31:21,700
Bring the carpet.

836
01:31:22,170 --> 01:31:23,880
Why can't -a we get out here?

837
01:31:24,170 --> 01:31:25,550
No-a carpet.

838
01:31:25,760 --> 01:31:26,920
Who cares?

839
01:31:27,220 --> 01:31:30,260
Me, Napaloni, I never get out
without a carpet.

840
01:31:37,280 --> 01:31:38,610
Lay it down here. Quick.

841
01:31:38,820 --> 01:31:40,700
- It's going back.
- What?

842
01:31:50,090 --> 01:31:52,340
Let's get out while it's stopping.

843
01:31:52,600 --> 01:31:53,680
Shut up!

844
01:32:01,070 --> 01:32:02,900
Take it away!

845
01:32:03,200 --> 01:32:06,200
Stay here
until they've made up their minds.

846
01:32:12,460 --> 01:32:14,710
You got-a da carpet. Put it down!

847
01:32:21,020 --> 01:32:22,190
Here he is.

848
01:32:24,320 --> 01:32:25,860
- My friend!
- Napaloni!

849
01:32:29,580 --> 01:32:34,130
This is indeed a pleasure.
Welcome to Tomainia. This way.

850
01:32:34,380 --> 01:32:35,620
Pictures!

851
01:32:36,010 --> 01:32:37,800
Sure. Salute!

852
01:32:38,300 --> 01:32:39,630
Another, please.

853
01:32:39,970 --> 01:32:42,850
This is a pleasure,
my friend Hynkel.

854
01:32:43,270 --> 01:32:44,520
You want another?

855
01:32:45,320 --> 01:32:46,480
There.

856
01:32:55,290 --> 01:32:58,290
Where's -a my ambassador?
Hello, Spook.

857
01:32:58,710 --> 01:33:01,340
How do you feel?
Look after mamma.

858
01:33:01,600 --> 01:33:03,390
Hynky, did you meet-a my wife?

859
01:33:04,020 --> 01:33:05,730
That's her. Let's go.

860
01:33:07,110 --> 01:33:10,310
Tomainia... very nice, very nice.

861
01:33:29,690 --> 01:33:31,400
Your clock is-a slow.

862
01:33:32,150 --> 01:33:33,480
This way.

863
01:33:57,860 --> 01:33:59,440
It's -a very nice people.

864
01:34:00,120 --> 01:34:02,160
The people are very nice.

865
01:34:02,580 --> 01:34:03,490
Thank you.

866
01:34:05,580 --> 01:34:07,080
He's my husband!

867
01:34:07,290 --> 01:34:10,500
You make a mistake!
You make a big-a mistake!

868
01:34:13,390 --> 01:34:17,140
Napaloni's army shall not invade
Osterlich. It belongs to me!

869
01:34:17,440 --> 01:34:20,190
We shall not discuss
the Osterlich situation.

870
01:34:20,400 --> 01:34:23,900
This interview is to impress on him
the force of your personality.

871
01:34:24,530 --> 01:34:26,780
To make him feel your superiority.

872
01:34:28,420 --> 01:34:30,490
Napaloni
is aggressive, domineering.

873
01:34:30,800 --> 01:34:32,750
We must put him in his place.

874
01:34:33,050 --> 01:34:33,960
But how?

875
01:34:34,260 --> 01:34:35,840
By means of psychology.

876
01:34:36,140 --> 01:34:38,810
By making him feel inferior.

877
01:34:39,100 --> 01:34:40,730
This can be done subtly.

878
01:34:41,320 --> 01:34:43,060
For instance,

879
01:34:43,320 --> 01:34:46,360
I have arranged
that he'll be looking up at you,

880
01:34:46,660 --> 01:34:48,150
you looking down at him.

881
01:34:48,410 --> 01:34:50,870
His position will be inferior.

882
01:34:52,960 --> 01:34:56,630
Then again we shall seat him
here beside your bust

883
01:34:57,180 --> 01:35:00,350
so that if you relax
that will always be glaring at him.

884
01:35:03,270 --> 01:35:04,220
Where is he now?

885
01:35:04,520 --> 01:35:05,440
Resting.

886
01:35:05,730 --> 01:35:09,900
I have arranged that he will enter
from the far end of the room.

887
01:35:10,530 --> 01:35:12,530
Another psychological triumph.

888
01:35:12,830 --> 01:35:16,030
He will have the embarrassment
of walking the entire floor.

889
01:35:22,300 --> 01:35:25,430
<i>Signor Napaloni
is now leaving his room.</i>

890
01:35:25,770 --> 01:35:28,100
He's coming.
Quick, give me a flower.

891
01:35:28,730 --> 01:35:30,890
At all times
be above him, before him.

892
01:35:31,240 --> 01:35:33,730
Entering or leaving
you must be first.

893
01:35:39,960 --> 01:35:41,420
Hello, Hynky!

894
01:35:46,010 --> 01:35:47,180
How are you feel?

895
01:35:52,320 --> 01:35:54,190
My brother dictate!

896
01:35:54,820 --> 01:35:58,610
You're a nice-a little man.
I'm so glad to see you again.

897
01:36:00,330 --> 01:36:02,320
And my friend the Garbitsch!

898
01:36:04,130 --> 01:36:06,540
This is a lovely place.

899
01:36:06,760 --> 01:36:08,750
I feel-a fine.

900
01:36:08,970 --> 01:36:12,060
I just had a nice cold shower.
When you have the plumbing fixed

901
01:36:12,440 --> 01:36:13,630
it'll be in good shape.

902
01:36:15,230 --> 01:36:16,730
Won't you sit down?

903
01:36:39,780 --> 01:36:43,030
Well, Hynky,
my dictator friend, you.

904
01:36:48,330 --> 01:36:49,880
I must be a-growing!

905
01:36:51,420 --> 01:36:53,750
What do they give me? A baby stool?

906
01:37:02,650 --> 01:37:05,610
This is not for me.
I like it better upstairs.

907
01:37:05,910 --> 01:37:09,110
Garbitsch, this is a lovely country.
Very nice-a people.

908
01:37:09,370 --> 01:37:11,660
I thought the public enthusiastic.

909
01:37:12,040 --> 01:37:14,330
Sure. They like to see new faces.

910
01:37:17,470 --> 01:37:21,050
I'm sorry for the mishap
that occurred to Madam Napaloni.

911
01:37:21,520 --> 01:37:22,380
What's that?

912
01:37:23,190 --> 01:37:27,060
I'm sorry for the Napaloni
that occurred at the... at...

913
01:37:27,990 --> 01:37:30,230
Madam Napaloni at the station.

914
01:37:31,030 --> 01:37:34,370
She's not used to public life.
She can't take it.

915
01:37:34,670 --> 01:37:35,620
Match.

916
01:37:36,500 --> 01:37:37,420
I'm sorry...

917
01:37:37,630 --> 01:37:40,880
Don't apologise. I find-a one.

918
01:37:42,850 --> 01:37:45,850
I'm simply crazy about this palace.

919
01:37:46,100 --> 01:37:48,860
Ivory and gold.
A lovely combination.

920
01:37:49,110 --> 01:37:51,190
Gets away
from that gingerbread idea.

921
01:37:51,490 --> 01:37:54,860
Tell me something, Garbitsch,
what's on the programme?

922
01:37:55,240 --> 01:37:56,950
The grand ball this evening.

923
01:37:58,710 --> 01:38:00,580
And a review of the army.

924
01:38:00,880 --> 01:38:02,420
That won't take-a long!

925
01:38:02,720 --> 01:38:03,960
I'm afraid it will.

926
01:38:04,260 --> 01:38:06,420
So you got a big army, huh?

927
01:38:07,020 --> 01:38:08,390
Modesty forbids.

928
01:38:09,730 --> 01:38:11,350
Seems I've heard about it.

929
01:38:11,650 --> 01:38:13,610
I think I'll get me a shave.

930
01:38:13,900 --> 01:38:14,940
We have a barbershop.

931
01:38:15,280 --> 01:38:16,860
Is that so?

932
01:38:17,280 --> 01:38:21,330
You look blue under the gills.
What do you say we go together?

933
01:38:21,620 --> 01:38:23,200
- Delighted.
- Good!

934
01:38:23,420 --> 01:38:25,130
Very well, this way.

935
01:38:34,610 --> 01:38:37,060
This is it. I can-a smell 'em.

936
01:38:44,920 --> 01:38:46,630
This is-a very sweet.

937
01:38:46,920 --> 01:38:48,080
It was the library.

938
01:38:48,380 --> 01:38:49,630
A good barbershop.

939
01:38:49,920 --> 01:38:51,800
- Too old-fashioned.
- Is that so?

940
01:38:52,050 --> 01:38:54,840
When I get shaved
I like something to look at.

941
01:38:55,100 --> 01:38:57,010
So I'm putting in glass walls.

942
01:38:57,270 --> 01:39:00,390
This way, I shall have a view
of the mountains.

943
01:39:00,860 --> 01:39:03,440
And this,
a view through the glass ceiling.

944
01:39:03,740 --> 01:39:05,650
- What's above?
- The ballroom.

945
01:39:07,830 --> 01:39:10,120
In my summer palace
I have a barbershop.

946
01:39:11,840 --> 01:39:13,170
Is that so?

947
01:39:15,930 --> 01:39:17,760
Also with glass walls.

948
01:39:18,020 --> 01:39:19,220
You don't tell me!

949
01:39:20,940 --> 01:39:22,730
With goldfish inside.

950
01:39:23,070 --> 01:39:26,360
Goldfish swimming inside the walls?
How do you feed them?

951
01:39:26,660 --> 01:39:30,360
You can't, they're all dead.
That's why I'm building a new one.

952
01:39:33,210 --> 01:39:35,670
- Very interesting!
- You like it?

953
01:39:40,680 --> 01:39:43,640
<i>The Hynkel stadium.
Before half a million spectators</i>

954
01:39:43,940 --> 01:39:47,990
<i>the greatest ever display of arms
marches by in review.</i>

955
01:39:48,240 --> 01:39:51,280
<i>Our beloved Phooey
and I'll-Dig-a-Ditchy are seated,</i>

956
01:39:51,580 --> 01:39:53,900
<i>thrilled by this historic event.</i>

957
01:39:54,750 --> 01:39:55,530
What?

958
01:39:55,750 --> 01:39:57,410
Nothing. I'm just chewing.

959
01:39:59,720 --> 01:40:01,130
Some peanuts?

960
01:40:02,180 --> 01:40:04,420
- I've had some.
- Good shape.

961
01:40:04,640 --> 01:40:05,560
Here you are, Spook.

962
01:40:05,770 --> 01:40:08,480
<i>Now passing,
Tomainia's heavy artillery.</i>

963
01:40:09,740 --> 01:40:11,020
It's all right.

964
01:40:11,400 --> 01:40:15,070
I want to show you my new bombing
planes. They're coming over.

965
01:40:15,330 --> 01:40:16,740
- Where from?
- Aroma.

966
01:40:16,960 --> 01:40:18,330
Aroma? That's 400 miles away.

967
01:40:18,630 --> 01:40:21,410
Right.
I don't know what's detaining them.

968
01:40:21,710 --> 01:40:24,250
<i>Now passing,
Tomainia's light artillery.</i>

969
01:40:29,440 --> 01:40:30,600
Very light!

970
01:40:31,110 --> 01:40:34,390
<i>And here come the armoured tanks,
the pride of Tomainia's army.</i>

971
01:40:34,700 --> 01:40:36,770
<i>The latest design, the last word</i>

972
01:40:36,990 --> 01:40:38,450
<i>in modern warfare.</i>

973
01:40:39,330 --> 01:40:43,380
Where's the propellers?
For going under the water!

974
01:40:43,670 --> 01:40:44,620
Under water?

975
01:40:44,920 --> 01:40:49,390
You never heard of tanks that go
under the water and fly up-a stairs?

976
01:40:49,600 --> 01:40:52,440
- What's that?
- Under the water and in the air.

977
01:40:52,730 --> 01:40:57,030
Obsolete now! We're concentrating
on flying dreadnoughts.

978
01:41:04,580 --> 01:41:06,160
- What's that?
- My planes!

979
01:41:06,420 --> 01:41:09,710
<i>Now passing, Hynkel's
flying division number 34.</i>

980
01:41:10,010 --> 01:41:11,420
Our planes!

981
01:41:16,810 --> 01:41:18,850
You're right. They're yours.

982
01:41:44,400 --> 01:41:48,490
Garbitsch!
The invasion of Osterlich.

983
01:41:48,790 --> 01:41:52,700
Our troops, tanks and guns
will be hidden along the border.

984
01:41:53,000 --> 01:41:55,760
To disarm suspicion,
you will go hunting.

985
01:41:56,050 --> 01:41:58,590
Then you will show up
at Pretzelburg,

986
01:41:58,890 --> 01:42:02,590
meet the army, step into a car
and cross over into Osterlich.

987
01:42:02,900 --> 01:42:05,440
Herring and I
will be waiting at the capital.

988
01:42:05,730 --> 01:42:07,980
First Napaloni must remove
his troops.

989
01:42:08,240 --> 01:42:09,480
To be decided tonight.

990
01:42:09,820 --> 01:42:10,990
Where is Napaloni?

991
01:42:11,240 --> 01:42:12,320
I'll look for him.

992
01:42:12,620 --> 01:42:16,460
It might be advisable for you
to dance with Madam Napaloni.

993
01:42:18,210 --> 01:42:19,290
It'll carry weight.

994
01:42:19,590 --> 01:42:21,250
You mean I will!

995
01:42:25,270 --> 01:42:27,310
You find him!
And let me know at once.

996
01:42:32,240 --> 01:42:34,990
- Madam Napaloni...
- Your Excellency!

997
01:42:37,000 --> 01:42:37,860
Why so triste?

998
01:42:38,120 --> 01:42:39,870
Because I no speak.

999
01:42:40,130 --> 01:42:42,370
No? May I have the pleasure?

1000
01:42:43,510 --> 01:42:44,840
Allow me.

1001
01:43:15,900 --> 01:43:19,150
Madam, your dancing was superb.

1002
01:43:19,410 --> 01:43:20,270
Excellent.

1003
01:43:20,660 --> 01:43:21,690
Very good.

1004
01:43:22,330 --> 01:43:23,320
Good.

1005
01:43:36,560 --> 01:43:38,440
- My dear Adenoid.
- Benzino!

1006
01:43:38,650 --> 01:43:39,900
I've been looking for you.

1007
01:43:40,190 --> 01:43:42,320
Let's go to some quiet place

1008
01:43:42,620 --> 01:43:44,570
where we can talk-a things over.

1009
01:43:44,790 --> 01:43:48,200
- As you wish.
- An excellent idea. To the buffet!

1010
01:43:48,420 --> 01:43:49,750
Of course, this way.

1011
01:44:08,540 --> 01:44:10,200
There's a Tomainian proverb...

1012
01:44:16,010 --> 01:44:18,130
Funny. I wish I understand it.

1013
01:44:18,550 --> 01:44:19,800
Now about the border.

1014
01:44:20,100 --> 01:44:20,930
Yes. No problem.

1015
01:44:21,230 --> 01:44:22,890
It should be no trouble.

1016
01:44:23,270 --> 01:44:24,900
- What's the matter?
- Wait.

1017
01:44:29,280 --> 01:44:30,690
You, too. Out!

1018
01:44:35,830 --> 01:44:36,780
Out.

1019
01:44:49,530 --> 01:44:51,850
- So... the border question.
- Yes.

1020
01:44:52,070 --> 01:44:54,570
It's just a matter of detail.
Formalities.

1021
01:44:54,870 --> 01:44:55,740
Strawberries!

1022
01:44:56,040 --> 01:44:58,740
- Have you any English mustard?
- English mustard.

1023
01:44:58,960 --> 01:45:00,340
- That's da hot-a stuff?
- Very hot.

1024
01:45:00,550 --> 01:45:01,420
Good shape.

1025
01:45:01,420 --> 01:45:02,290
Cream.

1026
01:45:03,340 --> 01:45:06,350
Hynky, I'm going to make this
very simple.

1027
01:45:06,640 --> 01:45:09,260
You agree not to invade Osterlich,

1028
01:45:09,560 --> 01:45:11,110
I agree not to invade Osterlich.

1029
01:45:11,360 --> 01:45:13,980
We sign, then I remove
my troops from the border.

1030
01:45:14,280 --> 01:45:16,150
When your troops
are gone, I sign.

1031
01:45:16,410 --> 01:45:17,440
That's -a right.

1032
01:45:18,990 --> 01:45:21,120
Just a minute,
you don't understand.

1033
01:45:21,370 --> 01:45:24,250
First we sign,
then I remove-a da troops.

1034
01:45:24,500 --> 01:45:27,460
- Precisely. I sign after.
- Just a minute.

1035
01:45:28,140 --> 01:45:29,720
Hey, Spook, treaty.

1036
01:45:30,430 --> 01:45:31,350
Hold-a dis.

1037
01:45:32,140 --> 01:45:35,310
Now, look, you sign-a
dis treaty first.

1038
01:45:35,570 --> 01:45:37,730
Then I remove my troops after.

1039
01:45:38,030 --> 01:45:39,190
Why are we arguing?

1040
01:45:39,450 --> 01:45:40,820
You said I remove first.

1041
01:45:41,120 --> 01:45:43,200
I can't sign while they're there.

1042
01:45:43,460 --> 01:45:45,750
- I won't remove them till you sign.
- Why not?

1043
01:45:45,960 --> 01:45:48,880
- Why should I?
- Osterlich is a free country!

1044
01:45:49,090 --> 01:45:50,800
Your soldiers are there.

1045
01:45:51,180 --> 01:45:53,470
And they'll stay until you sign.

1046
01:45:53,680 --> 01:45:55,010
I'll blow them off.

1047
01:45:55,850 --> 01:45:57,510
This won't get us anywhere.

1048
01:45:58,150 --> 01:46:00,480
To quote an old Latin phrase...

1049
01:46:03,700 --> 01:46:04,480
Strawberries!

1050
01:46:04,870 --> 01:46:07,540
Where's -a my sandwich?
Another one!

1051
01:46:08,630 --> 01:46:11,460
I don't get this treatment
in my own joint!

1052
01:46:11,760 --> 01:46:13,920
Can't we discuss this
without passion?

1053
01:46:14,220 --> 01:46:16,550
I'm not-a passionate. I'm just...

1054
01:46:16,770 --> 01:46:18,890
I want him to sign the treaty.

1055
01:46:19,310 --> 01:46:22,770
What would my people think,
signing such a treaty

1056
01:46:23,070 --> 01:46:25,060
when your soldiers
are on the border?

1057
01:46:25,320 --> 01:46:27,150
I won't move until you sign!

1058
01:46:27,410 --> 01:46:30,030
Not until you clear the border
will I sign!

1059
01:46:30,330 --> 01:46:31,280
Then they remain.

1060
01:46:31,540 --> 01:46:32,620
Then I kick them off.

1061
01:46:32,920 --> 01:46:36,370
One move from you and my artillery
will blow you to pieces!

1062
01:46:36,680 --> 01:46:40,300
And my aeroplanes will bomb
your artillery like that!

1063
01:46:40,600 --> 01:46:42,510
You want-a start a world war?

1064
01:46:42,810 --> 01:46:45,220
You and the world
I'll throw in the ocean!

1065
01:47:03,180 --> 01:47:04,090
Strawberries!

1066
01:47:04,180 --> 01:47:06,260
Your Excellency, we have...

1067
01:47:28,230 --> 01:47:30,470
I got-a my guns here in the pass

1068
01:47:30,770 --> 01:47:33,020
and I'll blow him to pieces.

1069
01:47:37,280 --> 01:47:39,490
What's the matter? What ails you?

1070
01:47:40,210 --> 01:47:41,320
This isn't like you.

1071
01:47:41,580 --> 01:47:44,840
Hey, Garbitsch, come here.

1072
01:47:45,460 --> 01:47:46,840
What's with Hynky?

1073
01:47:47,130 --> 01:47:48,680
Mustard on his strawberries.

1074
01:47:49,510 --> 01:47:51,810
What else can you expect
from Hynky?

1075
01:48:00,120 --> 01:48:02,030
My little bambino!

1076
01:48:15,640 --> 01:48:16,430
The Bacterian...

1077
01:48:16,730 --> 01:48:17,680
Tomainia...

1078
01:48:19,320 --> 01:48:21,440
You cannot treat Bacteria this way.

1079
01:48:21,740 --> 01:48:26,070
I'll take the Bacterian people
and tear them apart, like this!

1080
01:48:26,330 --> 01:48:29,870
Look what he's doing!
It's an insult to my people!

1081
01:48:31,510 --> 01:48:33,920
He's -a tearing spaghetti!

1082
01:48:34,220 --> 01:48:36,300
He sign-a the treaty
or we have a war!

1083
01:48:37,810 --> 01:48:40,770
Give me a-something!
Quick, give me a-something!

1084
01:48:44,910 --> 01:48:47,150
- I have an appointment.
- What's this?

1085
01:48:47,370 --> 01:48:49,780
Press.
How's the conference progressing?

1086
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:52,450
Very successfully.
How did you get in?

1087
01:48:54,210 --> 01:48:55,620
How did he get here?

1088
01:48:56,220 --> 01:48:59,500
You know the regulations
about reporters.

1089
01:48:59,720 --> 01:49:03,720
No one is to enter the palace
under any circumstances, understand?

1090
01:49:07,490 --> 01:49:10,940
There are minor details
to be cleaned up...

1091
01:49:12,290 --> 01:49:14,000
Excuse me, we're busy.

1092
01:49:21,140 --> 01:49:23,760
The whole world
will know we're fighting!

1093
01:49:23,980 --> 01:49:26,270
- So what?
- Can't we come to an agreement?

1094
01:49:26,520 --> 01:49:27,470
When he signs.

1095
01:49:27,770 --> 01:49:28,640
I sign nothing.

1096
01:49:28,940 --> 01:49:31,520
I must speak to you alone.
Do you mind?

1097
01:49:31,780 --> 01:49:33,240
Mind? I don't mind!

1098
01:49:33,490 --> 01:49:34,990
Sign! Sign!

1099
01:49:35,200 --> 01:49:36,280
He'll have the advantage.

1100
01:49:36,580 --> 01:49:38,540
It's a mere scrap of paper.

1101
01:49:38,830 --> 01:49:42,700
When his troops are off the border,
we can move in.

1102
01:49:44,600 --> 01:49:45,430
I'll sign.

1103
01:49:45,680 --> 01:49:47,560
What? Hold-a this.

1104
01:49:47,770 --> 01:49:51,390
Ah, my little Hynky!
My dictator brother!

1105
01:49:51,690 --> 01:49:53,730
I knew we have-a no trouble.

1106
01:49:59,910 --> 01:50:03,000
Two prisoners
escaped in officers' uniforms.

1107
01:50:03,540 --> 01:50:05,790
Sound the alarm!
Two prisoners escaped.

1108
01:50:24,580 --> 01:50:26,330
The planes are searching for us.

1109
01:50:26,630 --> 01:50:27,490
The woods.

1110
01:50:27,800 --> 01:50:30,120
No, the open.
The border's that way.

1111
01:50:32,140 --> 01:50:34,260
The invasion of Osterlich.

1112
01:50:35,520 --> 01:50:37,980
Now or never.

1113
01:50:43,830 --> 01:50:44,860
Ducks.

1114
01:50:50,420 --> 01:50:51,670
Did you hear that?

1115
01:50:52,010 --> 01:50:54,250
It came from over there.

1116
01:51:16,130 --> 01:51:18,810
A yodeller.
Where did you get that outfit?

1117
01:51:19,010 --> 01:51:21,090
- What?
- Don't answer back!

1118
01:51:22,940 --> 01:51:26,190
Where's Schultz?
You won't talk, eh?

1119
01:51:26,440 --> 01:51:28,940
- He will when we get him to camp.
- Come on.

1120
01:51:31,290 --> 01:51:34,660
There it is.
The village of Pretzelburg.

1121
01:51:36,880 --> 01:51:39,500
If we can pass through there
we're safe.

1122
01:51:39,800 --> 01:51:40,750
Through the woods?

1123
01:51:41,050 --> 01:51:44,090
They're swarming with soldiers.
They'd suspect us at once.

1124
01:51:44,810 --> 01:51:47,680
If you see anyone,
don't look right or left.

1125
01:51:47,980 --> 01:51:50,610
We must bluff our way through.

1126
01:51:51,450 --> 01:51:52,650
Here they come.

1127
01:52:01,800 --> 01:52:03,340
Can you see what they're doing?

1128
01:52:06,600 --> 01:52:09,350
- Looking this way.
- Keep going!

1129
01:52:12,480 --> 01:52:15,190
They're following us. Shall we run?

1130
01:52:15,450 --> 01:52:16,690
Certainly not.

1131
01:52:17,030 --> 01:52:17,820
Just a little bit?

1132
01:52:18,120 --> 01:52:19,320
Keep walking!

1133
01:52:21,500 --> 01:52:23,240
We could walk faster.

1134
01:52:25,550 --> 01:52:26,790
Make up your mind.

1135
01:52:37,610 --> 01:52:38,730
Slow down?

1136
01:52:39,030 --> 01:52:40,530
- No!
- There's no hurry.

1137
01:52:46,000 --> 01:52:47,200
He's here!

1138
01:52:47,760 --> 01:52:49,800
Sound assembly!

1139
01:52:59,900 --> 01:53:02,310
Attention!

1140
01:53:03,120 --> 01:53:05,410
Present arms!

1141
01:53:09,790 --> 01:53:10,830
Turn back?

1142
01:53:11,130 --> 01:53:12,380
No, keep going!

1143
01:53:13,970 --> 01:53:15,710
Hail Hynkel!

1144
01:53:18,310 --> 01:53:20,980
Your Excellency,
everything is under control.

1145
01:53:21,480 --> 01:53:22,600
- Good.
- Good.

1146
01:53:22,820 --> 01:53:26,320
I have been in communication
with Marshal Herring in Osterlich.

1147
01:53:26,620 --> 01:53:30,400
The route is well guarded. Behind us
are 200 tanks, 50 armoured cars

1148
01:53:30,620 --> 01:53:32,420
and 500 machine-guns.

1149
01:53:33,590 --> 01:53:34,830
- Good.
- Good.

1150
01:53:35,050 --> 01:53:36,540
Are we ready to start?

1151
01:53:36,760 --> 01:53:37,790
- Yes.
- Yes.

1152
01:53:39,220 --> 01:53:40,550
Gentlemen.

1153
01:53:46,990 --> 01:53:49,660
Schultz,
I'm happy you're with us again.

1154
01:53:49,870 --> 01:53:50,950
Thank you.

1155
01:53:58,170 --> 01:53:59,040
Where are we going?

1156
01:53:59,300 --> 01:54:01,380
You're invading Osterlich.

1157
01:55:19,070 --> 01:55:20,730
They're coming.

1158
01:56:17,000 --> 01:56:17,830
Your Excellency.

1159
01:56:18,590 --> 01:56:20,630
The world awaits your words.

1160
01:56:53,400 --> 01:56:55,310
What's happened?
He looks strange.

1161
01:56:55,570 --> 01:56:57,150
What's Schultz doing here?

1162
01:56:57,410 --> 01:56:58,440
Pardoned, I suppose.

1163
01:57:26,040 --> 01:57:28,000
His Excellency Herr Garbitsch,

1164
01:57:28,210 --> 01:57:31,090
Secretary of the Interior,
Minister of Propaganda...

1165
01:57:36,150 --> 01:57:38,100
<i>Corona veniet delectis.</i>

1166
01:57:38,320 --> 01:57:40,520
Victory shall come to the worthy.

1167
01:57:41,320 --> 01:57:44,410
Today, democracy, liberty
and equality

1168
01:57:44,660 --> 01:57:46,450
are words to fool the people.

1169
01:57:46,750 --> 01:57:49,210
No nation
can progress with such ideas.

1170
01:57:49,460 --> 01:57:53,160
They stand in the way of action.
Therefore, we abolish them.

1171
01:57:54,090 --> 01:57:58,480
In the future, each man will serve
the state with absolute obedience.

1172
01:57:58,770 --> 01:58:00,650
Let him who refuses beware!

1173
01:58:01,190 --> 01:58:05,060
Citizenship will be taken away
from all Jews and non-Aryans.

1174
01:58:05,370 --> 01:58:08,530
They are inferior and therefore
enemies of the state.

1175
01:58:08,830 --> 01:58:12,330
It is the duty of all true Aryans
to hate and despise them.

1176
01:58:13,420 --> 01:58:16,290
This nation
is annexed to the Tomainian Empire,

1177
01:58:16,550 --> 01:58:20,170
and the people will obey the laws
bestowed on us by our great leader,

1178
01:58:21,770 --> 01:58:25,720
the Dictator of Tomainia,
the conqueror of Osterlich,

1179
01:58:26,030 --> 01:58:29,810
the future Emperor of the World!

1180
01:58:30,990 --> 01:58:32,490
You must speak.

1181
01:58:33,960 --> 01:58:34,910
I can't.

1182
01:58:35,210 --> 01:58:37,920
You must. It's our only hope.

1183
01:58:40,760 --> 01:58:41,790
Hope...

1184
01:59:29,890 --> 01:59:33,260
I'm sorry
but I don't want to be an emperor.

1185
01:59:33,560 --> 01:59:35,060
That's not my business.

1186
01:59:35,650 --> 01:59:38,060
I don't want to rule
or conquer anyone.

1187
01:59:38,320 --> 01:59:39,980
I should like to help everyone:

1188
01:59:40,280 --> 01:59:43,490
Jew, gentile, black man, white.

1189
01:59:43,790 --> 01:59:47,080
We all want to help one another.
Human beings are like that.

1190
01:59:47,380 --> 01:59:50,380
We want to live by each other's
happiness, not misery.

1191
01:59:50,680 --> 01:59:52,920
We don't want to hate one another.

1192
01:59:53,220 --> 01:59:54,470
In this world,

1193
01:59:54,730 --> 01:59:58,180
the good earth is rich
and can provide for everyone.

1194
01:59:58,480 --> 02:00:01,240
The way of life can be free
and beautiful

1195
02:00:01,530 --> 02:00:03,360
but we have lost the way.

1196
02:00:03,700 --> 02:00:06,110
Greed has poisoned men's souls,

1197
02:00:06,410 --> 02:00:08,410
has barricaded the world with hate,

1198
02:00:08,710 --> 02:00:11,460
has goose-stepped us into bloodshed.

1199
02:00:11,710 --> 02:00:14,880
We have developed speed
but have shut ourselves in.

1200
02:00:15,180 --> 02:00:17,890
Machinery has left us in want.

1201
02:00:18,190 --> 02:00:22,020
Our knowledge has made us cynical,
our cleverness, hard and unkind.

1202
02:00:22,320 --> 02:00:24,940
We think too much
and feel too little.

1203
02:00:25,240 --> 02:00:27,700
More than machinery
we need humanity.

1204
02:00:27,990 --> 02:00:31,370
More than cleverness
we need kindness and gentleness.

1205
02:00:31,670 --> 02:00:35,710
Without these qualities, life will
be violent and all will be lost...

1206
02:00:35,970 --> 02:00:38,460
The aeroplane and radio
have brought us closer.

1207
02:00:38,760 --> 02:00:41,770
These inventions cry out
for the goodness in man,

1208
02:00:42,060 --> 02:00:45,150
cry out for universal brotherhood,
for the unity of us all.

1209
02:00:45,440 --> 02:00:48,320
Even now
my voice is reaching millions,

1210
02:00:48,620 --> 02:00:51,650
millions of despairing men,
women and children,

1211
02:00:51,910 --> 02:00:54,450
victims of a system
that makes men torture

1212
02:00:54,750 --> 02:00:56,830
and imprison innocent people.

1213
02:00:57,130 --> 02:01:00,300
To those who can hear me I say,
do not despair.

1214
02:01:00,590 --> 02:01:03,630
The misery upon us
is but the passing of greed,

1215
02:01:03,890 --> 02:01:07,390
the bitterness of men who fear
the way of human progress.

1216
02:01:07,690 --> 02:01:10,810
The hate of men will pass,
and dictators die,

1217
02:01:11,110 --> 02:01:14,450
and the power they took
will return to the people.

1218
02:01:14,740 --> 02:01:18,660
So long as men die
liberty will never perish.

1219
02:01:19,840 --> 02:01:22,460
Soldiers,
don't give yourselves to brutes,

1220
02:01:22,760 --> 02:01:24,670
men who despise you, enslave you,

1221
02:01:24,930 --> 02:01:28,600
regiment your lives,
tell you what to think and feel,

1222
02:01:28,850 --> 02:01:32,850
who drill you, treat you like cattle
and use you as cannon fodder.

1223
02:01:33,150 --> 02:01:35,690
Don't give yourselves to these men,

1224
02:01:35,950 --> 02:01:39,280
machine men with machine minds
and machine hearts.

1225
02:01:39,580 --> 02:01:43,170
You are not machines,
you are not cattle, you are men!

1226
02:01:43,460 --> 02:01:45,500
You have
the love of humanity in you.

1227
02:01:45,760 --> 02:01:49,630
Don't hate. Only the unloved
and the unnatural hate.

1228
02:01:49,930 --> 02:01:53,220
Soldiers, don't fight for slavery,
fight for liberty!

1229
02:01:53,520 --> 02:01:57,060
St. Luke says,
"The Kingdom of God is within man."

1230
02:01:57,360 --> 02:02:00,820
Not in one man nor a group of men,
but in all men. In you!

1231
02:02:01,120 --> 02:02:04,410
You have the power
to create machines,

1232
02:02:04,620 --> 02:02:06,040
the power to create happiness.

1233
02:02:06,340 --> 02:02:09,670
You have the power to make
this life free and beautiful,

1234
02:02:09,930 --> 02:02:12,090
to make this life
a wonderful adventure.

1235
02:02:12,390 --> 02:02:15,260
In the name of democracy,
let us use that power.

1236
02:02:15,560 --> 02:02:19,100
Let us all unite,
let us fight for a new world,

1237
02:02:19,400 --> 02:02:22,190
a world
that will give men a chance to work,

1238
02:02:22,490 --> 02:02:25,360
that will give youth a future
and old age security.

1239
02:02:25,660 --> 02:02:28,420
Promising these things,
brutes have risen.

1240
02:02:28,710 --> 02:02:32,250
But they lie! They do not fulfil
that promise. They never will!

1241
02:02:32,550 --> 02:02:36,170
Dictators free themselves
but they enslave the people.

1242
02:02:36,470 --> 02:02:39,350
Now let us fight
to fulfil that promise!

1243
02:02:39,650 --> 02:02:43,810
Let us fight to free the world,
to do away with national barriers,

1244
02:02:44,110 --> 02:02:47,570
to do away with greed,
with hate and intolerance.

1245
02:02:47,830 --> 02:02:49,870
Let us fight for a world of reason,

1246
02:02:50,160 --> 02:02:54,630
a world where science and progress
will lead to the happiness of all.

1247
02:02:54,880 --> 02:02:57,290
Soldiers, in the name of democracy,

1248
02:02:57,600 --> 02:02:59,300
let us unite!

1249
02:03:24,140 --> 02:03:25,220
Hannah,

1250
02:03:26,360 --> 02:03:27,770
can you hear me?

1251
02:03:28,980 --> 02:03:32,650
Wherever you are, look up, Hannah.

1252
02:03:33,490 --> 02:03:37,790
The clouds are lifting,
the sun is breaking through.

1253
02:03:38,500 --> 02:03:41,290
We are coming out of the darkness

1254
02:03:41,880 --> 02:03:44,040
into a new world,

1255
02:03:44,390 --> 02:03:46,010
a kindlier world,

1256
02:03:46,430 --> 02:03:49,930
where men will rise
above their hate, their greed

1257
02:03:50,230 --> 02:03:51,640
and their brutality.

1258
02:03:52,440 --> 02:03:53,940
Look up, Hannah.

1259
02:03:54,150 --> 02:03:58,950
The soul of man
has been given wings.

1260
02:03:59,960 --> 02:04:02,000
He is flying into the rainbow,

1261
02:04:02,290 --> 02:04:05,550
into the light of hope,
into the future,

1262
02:04:05,840 --> 02:04:09,300
the glorious future
that belongs to you,

1263
02:04:09,600 --> 02:04:12,520
to me and to all of us.

1264
02:04:12,850 --> 02:04:15,610
Look up, Hannah. Look up!

1265
02:04:42,450 --> 02:04:43,860
Did you hear that?

1266
02:04:46,160 --> 02:04:47,280
Listen...

